<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BankAgency-Probe     04-02 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Agency-Probe,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Bank Official Sought FBI Probe of Critic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New Jersey congressman says ``something just
doesn't smell right'' about a federal banking agency's request for
an FBI check of one of its critics.
   The request to the FBI from a Federal Home Loan Bank Board
official ``smacks of a way of life that seems to be more
appropriate to life in Latin America than it does in the United
States,'' Rep. James Florio, D-N.J., said Friday.
   The FBI check was revealed by an internal bank board
investigation requested by Florio, chairman of the House Energy and
Commerce consumer protection subcommittee.
   The report, by bank board Inspector General Paul Gibbons,
disclosed that the office of Rosemary Stewart, bank board
enforcement director, asked the FBI on Aug. 17 to check on William
Juliano, a Mount Laurel, N.J., developer.
   The FBI returned the request, which listed only Juliano's name
and address, stamped ``insufficient information,'' and Ms. Stewart
decided not to pursue the matter.
   Because of Juliano's criticism, Florio had asked for an
investigation of the Federal Asset Disposition Association, the arm
of the Bank Board that manages and sells real estate from bankrupt
savings and loans.
   FADA was under attack from Juliano, other business people and
members of Congress for reported mismanagement and conflicts of
interest.
   Juliano had threatened to bring a class action lawsuit against
FADA on behalf of disgruntled developers who believed they had been
poorly treated by the agency.
   Ms. Stewart told investigators she was asked in June to obtain
the FBI check from FADA General Counsel Robert J. Axley, who said
Juliano had made verbal threats and written nasty letters to then
FADA President Rosyln Payne.
   Axley told the investigators that Ms. Payne asked him to ``have
Juliano checked out'' after she received anonymous telephone calls
in the middle of the night to her unlisted home telephone.
   Axley said he subsequently received a tip that Juliano had ties
to organized crime. However, the bank board report said the tip
referred to someone with a different first name than Juliano's.
   After her request to the FBI was returned, Ms. Stewart said she
learned more about the nature of Juliano's dispute with FADA,
consulted her superiors at the bank board and decided it was not
appropriate for her to resubmit the query to the FBI.
   But Florio said, ``For the bank board to even contemplate
investigating a citizen for complaining raises a lot of questions.
... Something just doesn't smell right here.''
   Ms. Stewart did not immediately return telephone messages left
at her office Friday afternoon. There was no answer at Juliano's
office.
   Karl Hoyle, a bank board spokesman, said the agency acknowledges
that the request to the FBI should never have been made.
   ``Once we were aware of it, we indicated we didn't want that
pursued and after that it was not,'' he said. ``Rosemary, to her
credit, said `Maybe we're not supposed to be doing that sort of
thing.'''
   The bank board has also acknowledged that a law firm hired by
FADA engaged a private detective agency to look into Juliano's
finances.
   FBI spokesman William Carter said the FBI would not consider it
proper to investigate a government critic. The bureau's practice,
he said, is to ask for more information about the reason a
background check is requested and if the explanation is not
appropriate it can recommend administrative or disciplinary actions
against the person who made the request.
   Hoyle said Ms. Stewart has not been reprimanded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
