<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HashBash     04-02 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hash Bash,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>400 Get High On Pot Reform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 400 people huffed and puffed
Friday at the 17th annual Hash Bash, a spring rally for the
legalization of marijuana.
   Police made no arrests and issued no citations during the event
on the University of Michigan campus. University officials had
issued a permit for the event but emphasized they were not
endorsing it.
   Possession of small amounts of marijuana in Ann Arbor is
punishable by a $5 fine.
   ``I've been coming to this since I was a little boy,'' said a
29-year-old who called himself Jizmo Noodles and was one of the
first to light up. ``My first one was in 1973. It's a means of
expression, civil disobedience.''
   Noodles, carrying incense and wearing jeans, a T-shirt and a
denim vest with a peace sign, described himself as a ``student of
life.''
   Jon Gettman, assistant director of the National Organization for
the Reform of Marijuana Laws, or NORML, told the gathering that pot
smokers were tired of being labeled criminals.
   ``We're here for a lot of different reasons today,'' he said.
``A lot of people think that because this is April Fools' Day, that
this is some some kind of a joke. We are serious, very serious.''
   NORML wants marijuana legalized, with taxes on it used to
develop treatment centers for cocaine and heroin users.
   Mark Amicone, sophomore history major, said he started smoking
marijuana at 16. ``I got a late start,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
