<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Names     04-02 0772</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0807</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Douglas Edwards, one of the ``founding fathers''
of broadcast journalism, signed off after more than four decades on
the air by thanking his coworkers and his viewers during his last
TV appearance for CBS.
   ``And so ends the chapter of almost 46 years as this reporter
moves on along the journey,'' Edwards, 70, said on Friday's midday
``CBS Newsbreak.''
   ``A deep bow of gratitude, love and respect to the men and women
of CBS News and to the company for which they stand. To you out
there, thank you for honoring me with your presence in my audience,
and most of all for your voices, your most sweet voices. Douglas
Edwards, CBS News, New York.''
   Edwards was the nation's first nightly TV anchorman, preceding
Walter Cronkite in the job at CBS in 1948.
   Edwards joined CBS Radio in 1942, and was a member of Edward R.
Murrow's legendary London staff toward the end of World War II. He
also served as Paris bureau chief.
   Edwards' last radio broadcast was Friday night. At its close,
CBS News vice president Joe Dembo wished Edwards ``goodbye and
Godspeed,'' and CBS Evening News anchorman Dan Rather saluted him
as ``one of the founding fathers'' of broadcast journalism.
   President Reagan sent a congratulatory letter calling Edwards a
``consummate professional.''
   Edwards plans to move to Sarasota, Fla., and continue lecturing
on broadcast journalism while he starts work on a book.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Britt Ekland has given birth to her
third child, an 8-pound, 12-ounce boy named Thomas Jefferson Ekland
McDonnell, her manager says.
   The baby, born Thursday at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center, is Miss
Ekland's first child with husband James McDonnell, manager Paul
Cohen said Friday.
   Miss Ekland and McDonnell, former drummer for the Stray Cats
rock group have been married four years.
   Miss Ekland, 45, has appeared in more than 30 films, including
such movies as ``The Man With the Golden Gun.''
   Her other children are Victoria Sellers, 23, and Nickolai Edland
Adler, 14.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Neil Goldschmidt will play host next
week to an ex-boss _ former President Jimmy Carter.
   Carter is coming to Oregon to give a lecture at Linfield College
in nearby McMinnville, and plans to stay Wednesday night at the
governor's residence here, Goldschmidt spokesman Gregg Kantor said
Friday.
   Goldschmidt served as secretary of transportation under Carter.
   Carter also plans to spend some time vacationing in Oregon,
Kantor said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version also moving sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GREENBRAE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hall of Fame pitcher Vernon ``Lefty''
Gomez was hospitalized after complaining of chest pains, and was
expected to remain in the hospital for several days, a hospital
spokeswoman said.
   Gomez, 79, was in improved condition, Marin General Hospital
nursing supervisor Diana Rich said Friday night. ``He's doing very
well, but he'll be here awhile longer,'' she said.
   Gomez has a longstanding heart condition.
   He was driven to the hospital by his wife, June, from their home
in nearby Novato, 25 miles north of San Francisco.
   ``If he lets me drive him, he has to be sick,'' Mrs. Gomez said.
``Thirteen years ago he had a heart attack and he drove me to the
hospital. He said he didn't trust me to drive. Then he had a triple
bypass.''
   Gomez, a strong left-hander who pitched for 14 years in the
major leagues, all but one year with the New York Yankees, had a
career record of 189-102. He was 6-0 in appearances in five World
Series.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Performers Robert Cray, Albert Collins and Kim
Wilson of The Fabulous Thunderbirds are to headline a benefit
concert Sunday for Grammy-winning blues singer Koko Taylor, who was
injured in an auto accident.
   Miss Taylor, known as the ``Queen of the Blues,'' suffered
broken ribs and a broken collarbone in the Feb. 4 accident, which
also injured three band members.
   ``It was a disaster, but we are so fortunate to be alive,'' Miss
Taylor said in a telephone interview Friday from her Chicago home.
``I'm very thankful that so many people think so much of me to put
on this benefit.''
   Sunday's benefit will raise money to pay for the $40,000 in
medical bills, said Bruce Iglauer, president of Alligator Records,
who helped arrange the event at the Riviera Nightclub.
   Miss Taylor said she was unsure whether she'll be able to
attend. But she was grateful for the support, and for the thousands
of cards and letters she's received.
   ``It makes me know there are lots of people out there that
care,'' she said.
</TEXT>
