<HEAD>One Dies, 10 Wounded in Drive-By Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen in a passing car opened fire
indiscriminately on people gathered in several groups along a
street Friday night, killing one and wounding at least 10, police
said.
   Among the wounded was a 4-year-old boy shot four times, a
hospital spokeswoman said.
   The shooting started around 7:20 p.m. when several gunmen in a
car ``indiscriminately fired at people who were on a sidewalk,''
said Deputy Police Chief William Rathburn.
   At least 11 people initially were reported wounded, although
Rathburn said others may have been hit.
   Four people were taken to Los Angeles County-USC Medical Center,
where a 19-year-old man shot in the right side was pronounced dead,
said hospital spokeswoman Adelaida de la Certa.
   The 4-year-old boy was in serious but stable condition, Ms. de
la Certa said.
   A 29-year-old man hit in the right hand and right leg and a
20-year-old man shot in the left leg were both in fair condition.
   The other seven wounded were taken to other hospitals, she said.
   Drive-by shootings have become a problem in recent months in the
Los Angeles area. Police have attributed many of them to gang wars,
but did not say if Friday's shootings were gang-related.
