<HEAD>Koch Says Jackson as President Would Bankrupt U.S. in 3 Weeks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch says he disagrees with
Jesse Jackson on virtually every issue, but will vote for Jackson
if he is the Democratic presidential nominee.
   ``I think that in three weeks, based on all the social programs
we would be putting into effect (under Jackson), if you did
everything he said he wanted to do, we'd be in bankruptcy,'' Koch
said Friday. ``People know that's pie in the sky.''
   In response, Jackson's campaign manager, Jerry Austin, said Koch
has ``solidified his position in the national exaggeration hall of
fame.''
   Koch said Jackson is ``on the wrong side of every issue I know
of with two exceptions: drugs _ he's great in opposition to drugs _
and he's great in talking about the need for family responsibility
and particularly as it relates to education.
   ``On the economy, he's terrible. We'd be in bankruptcy.''
   Nevertheless, the mayor said, he'd vote for Jackson if he were
the nominee out of party loyalty and because ``he'd be better than
(Vice President George) Bush.''
   In Green Bay, Wis., Jackson told reporters he had not heard of
Koch's remarks. But when they were described to him he said,
``That's unfortunate. I should not dignify that statement.''
