<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Panama Bjt   04-02 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama, Bjt,0641</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jailed Opposition Leader Called ``Hostage''; U.S. Boosts Military
Presence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers were off the streets as
Easter weekend began and a jailed opposition leader's wife said her
husband was being held hostage in Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega's
effort to maintain power.
   Also Friday, the Pentagon said it was sending 1,300 more
military personnel to protect U.S. bases and thousands of American
residents, bringing to nearly 12,000 the number of U.S. troops in
Panama.
   Opposition leaders said they planned to meet today or Sunday to
decide whether to lift a 12-day-old general strike that has shut
down most commercial activity in an effort to oust Noriega,
Panama's de facto leader and heads of its 15,000-member Defense
Forces.
   Virtually all businesses were closed for Good Friday. The
general strike had eased earlier in the week, with groceries and
pharmacies reopening, reportedly under government pressure.
   In the United States, news reports said Reagan administration
officials had discussed trying to force Noriega from power through
military intervention, kidnapping or by arranging a coup.
   The general is under U.S. indictment on drug trafficking charges.
   Carlos Gonzalez de la Lastra, a top leader of the opposition
National Civic Crusade, spent his fifth day in jail Friday. Other
Crusade leaders and several journalists arrested with him Monday
had all been released by midday Tuesday.
   ``All legal efforts on his behalf have been useless,'' Vilma
Gonzalez de la Lastra told The Associated Press Friday night.
``They have not charged him, but they don't let him go.
   ``We consider Carlos a political hostage,'' she said of her
husband.
   The Pentagon said many of the U.S. personnel to be dispatched
next week are military police, but army helicopter units will be
included.
   The U.S. Southern Command, based in Panama, had about 600
security personnel among its 10,000 troopers before Washington
intensified its campaign for Noriega's removal.
   Over a 10-day period that ended March 24, the Pentagon
dispatched 670 more security personnel to Panama for the stated
purpose of protecting military facilities.
   Southern Command spokesman Col. Ronald Sconyers said the latest
troop increase was prompted by ``a longstanding look at what has
been going on down here.'' He said it was not made in anticipation
of an imminent departure of Noriega and any instability that might
follow.
   No evacuation plans have been discussed with the 45,000
Americans living in Panama, he added.
   Limitations on movement for U.S. military personnel were
decreased Friday to the lowest of four levels for the first time
since the crisis began Feb. 26, permitting them to move freely but
avoid crowds and demonstrations.
   Panamanian police patrols replaced soldiers Friday for the first
time since a failed March 16 coup attempt against Noriega. It was
an indication of how the city has quieted for the holiday weekend,
after weeks of protest.
   Banks have been closed since March 3, and Panamanians who had
cash appeared to be using it only for essentials.
   Despite rumors the decision to lift the strike had been made,
two Crusade leaders, Roberto Aleman and Luis Casco Arias, said that
was not the case.
   ``To the contrary, no decision on that will be made until we are
able to meet to discuss it,'' said Casco Arias.
   The National Council of Private Enterprise, an umbrella group of
business organizations, has decided to continue the stoppage,
Aleman said.
   Noriega supporters in the National Legislature ousted civilian
President Eric Arturo Delvalle on Feb. 26 after Delvalle tried to
fire the general.
   The United States subsequently froze Panamanian government
deposits in U.S. banks in an effort to drive out Noriega. The
shortage of money and a run on Panama's banks forced them to shut
down.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
