<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador     04-02 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Right-Wing Party Vows to Seek Nullification of Assembly Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The right-wing Nationalist
Republican Party has vowed to seek a nullification of the
Legislative Assembly elections, in which it fell short of a clear
majority by gaining 30 of the 60 seats.
   Party leaders accused the Central Elections Council of
manipulating the official results of the March 20 balloting, which
were announced Friday.
   The council said the party known by its Spanish acronym Arena
won 30 seats, President Jose Napoleon Duarte's centrist Christian
Democrat 23 and the conservative National Conciliation Party seven.
   Arena emerged as the strongest single party, replacing the
Christian Democrats, but its failure to win a majority could
produce a legislative deadlock during Duarte's final year in office.
   National Conciliation lawmakers were reported considering an
alignment with the Christian Democrats. That would give them the
balance of power on major issues and counter Arena's strength.
   In the outgoing Legislative Assembly, elected in March 1984, the
Christian Democrats had 33 seats and Arena 13.
   Mario Samayoa, president of the elections council and a director
of the Christian Democratic Party, said the final results presented
an ``interesting situation because no party will predominate.''
   He also said that while the computer count of votes for mayors
in the nation's 262 municipalities was not complete, it appeared
Arena candidates had won in 178 races.
   The elections council report was denounced by angry Arena
leaders, who earlier had claimed their party won 35 assembly seats
and a firm majority.
   On Tuesday, Arena removed its representative from the panel of
observers from the three major parties overseeing the vote count.
   Francisco Merino, the Arena representative, said the Christian
Democrat and National Conciliation delegates were trying to make a
``game of the vote tallies in order to change the results of the
elections.''
   Roberto d'Aubuisson, the former army major who founded Arena,
said the alliance would petition the council to nullify the
official results and if that was rejected the issue would be taken
to the Supreme Court.
   Three days after the election, d'Aubuisson had said ``we don't
want to promote violence. But we want to play clean and they won't
let us.''
   Samayoa said Friday that Arena would have to accept the results
and ``re-evaluate its positions.''
   The National Association for Private Enterprise declared it
would call a general strike if the elections council did not report
an Arena majority.
   Duarte, a staunch U.S. ally, was elected in 1984 and is barred
by the constitution from seeking another five year term next year.
   In the 1984 campaign he pledged to improve the economy and end
the 8-year-old war with leftist rebels.
   Arena had based its campaign this year on the continuing
conflict, unemployment estimated at 40 percent and inflation
running at an annual rate of 40 percent.
</TEXT>
