<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India-Sikhs     04-02 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gandhi Urged To Declare Emergency; 14 More Slain As Security
Stepped Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders in Punjab called on Prime
Minister Rajiv Gandhi to impose a state of emergency in their
northern state to quell violence by Sikh separatists that has
killed more than 100 people this week.
   Late Friday and early today, Sikh extremists killed 14 more
people in the Punjab state as police stepped up security on
Gandhi's orders, the United News of India reported.
   The prime minister also called the federally appointed Punjab
governor, S.S. Ray, to New Delhi today for urgent consultations on
the violence.
   In addition, police and paramilitary troops began stepping up
security on Pakistan' border with the state, where police say
smugglers have been moving large quantities of new weapons to the
Sikh extremists, UNI said.
   The latest killings raised to 111 the number of people who have
died in Punjab since Sunday in attacks blamed on militant Sikhs who
have since 1982 been waging a guerrilla war for a separate homeland.
   So far this year, more than 635 people have died in Punjab
state, including Hindus and moderate Sikhs. Sikh militants say they
are discriminated against by India's Hindu majority.
   Right-wing Hindu groups called for a general strike in Amritsar
District today to protest the killings. Residents of the Sikh holy
city of Amritsar said about half of the city's shops were shuttered
today, but government offices and schools remained open and
transportion was normal.
   Punjab leaders of Gandhi's Congress Party called Friday for the
state of emergency. They included Bhagwan Dass, vice president of
the state Congress Party's governing committee, two of the state
party's general secretaries and a former president.
   The federal government last month was empowered by Parliament to
impose an emergency in a single state to combat ``internal
disturbances.'' Under an emergency, the government would have the
authority to detain people without warrants, suspend press freedom
and take other steps against the militants.
   Sikhs, whose religion was formed about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam, make up less than 2 percent of
India's population of 800 million but are in a majority in Punjab.
   UNI said that eight Sikhs, four Hindus and two unidentified
people were killed overnight in three districts of Punjab by
suspected Sikh gunmen.
   Thirty-seven people were reported killed Thursday night and
Friday in the state, the worst one-day toll since March 4, when 45
people were reported slain in a single day, 34 of them at a
festival marking the Indian holiday of Holi.
</TEXT>
