<DOCNO> AP880402-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 0607EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Greece-Daedalus     04-02 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Daedalus,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human-Powered Flight Called Off At Last Moment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HERAKLION, Crete (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Breezy weather early today forced
organizers to scratch their attempt at a world-record human-powered
flight across the Aegean Sea by a cyclist-pilot in a flying machine
called the Daedalus.
   Windless weather is important for the 74-mile flight to the
island of Santorini and winds of nearly six miles an hour grounded
the silver-and-pink aircraft on a military runway at the last
moment.
   ``It's disappointing, but the wind seems to be a little too
strong,'' pilot Greg Zack, 26, a professional cyclist from
Wilmington, N.C., told reporters.
   The last-minute postponement illustrated just how unpredictable
the weather can be on this southern Greek island.
   Gusting winds and rain squalls delayed the first scheduled
flight of the Daedalus 88 on Wednesday.
   After nine days of blustery weather, conditions Thursday were
good enough to allow the five athlete pilots to take turns
test-flying the plane at speeds of around 14 miles per hour and
about 15 feet above the tarmac of the Greek air force base.
   A successful touchdown on Santorini (Thira) would more than
triple the exisiting record of 22.5 miles for straight-line
human-powered flight, set by Bryan Allen piloting the Gossamer
Albatross across the English channel in 1979.
   Built of high-tech composite materials _ graphite epoxy, kevlar
plastic fiber and mylar polystyrene film _ the Daedalus plane has a
huge 112-foot wingspan and resembles an outsized insect in flight.
   The flight in a fragile pedal-powered plane is aimed at
emulating Daedalus, the legendary craftsman who flapped his way
across the Aegean on wings of wax and feathers, according to a
3,500-year-old Greek myth.
   According to the myth, Daedalus made it safely across the Aegean
but his son Icarus flew too close to the sun and plummeted to his
death as his wings melted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880402-0026 </DOCNO>
