<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Stabbings     04-02 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stabbings,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Dead, Two Wounded In Archaeological Site Rampage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST CONSHOHOCKEN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man working at an archaeological
dig attacked co-workers, stabbing two women to death and injuring a
pregnant woman and her husband, police said.
   The suspect, identified as Arthur Faulkner and believed to be 40
to 45 years old, remained at large today, police said.
   Authorities said they had no motive for the stabbings Friday.
   Police temporarily shut down a nearby expressway and searched a
wooded area in this Philadelphia suburb after the man fled in a
pickup truck registered to one of the victims.
   The four graduate students were ``stabbed with a knife or other
sharp instrument,'' while working in a house where artifacts are
tested, police Capt. John Sheehan said. He refused to say whether a
weapon was recovered.
   Glenn W. Sheehan, 39, was stabbed several times. He ran from the
house to a neighbor's house, then to a construction site where the
archaeological dig was under way, according to witnesses.
   Sheehan was taken to Bryn Mawr Hospital with stab wounds of the
legs, arms and abdomen. He was in stable condition, hospital
officials said.
   His wife, 31-year-old Anne M. Jensen, was taken to Hahnemann
Hospital in Philadelphia, where she was treated for multiple stab
wounds to the back and internal injuries.
   She was in serious but stable condition, said an unidentified
hospital spokeswoman. Her fetus suffered no damage, the spokeswoman
said.
   The couple were working on their doctorates in anthropology at
Bryn Mawr College, college spokeswoman Catherine LaFarge said.
   The two slain women, also graduate students in anthropology and
archaeology, died of multiple stab wounds, Montgomery County
Coroner Dr. Theodore Garcia said.
   Lower Merion Township Police Lt. John Maloney identified them as
Clarice J. Dorner, 30, of Elk Grove Village, Ill., and Annaliese H.
Killoran, 22, of Lynn, Mass.
   WCAU-TV, quoting unidentified police sources, reported that
Faulkner was released from prison last October after serving time
for attempted rape.
   John Jensen, Anne Jensen's brother, said Faulkner was a former
convict who seemed interested in his work as a digger.
   ``I just couldn't believe it,'' said Jensen. ``I talked to him
yesterday. He was a solid worker; he never complained.''
</TEXT>
