<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 0709EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Philippines-Honasan 2ndLd-Writethru a0458 04-02 0815</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Honasan, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0458,0836</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Colonel Who Led Bloody Challenge To Aquino Escapes Custody</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Aquino saying Honasan was about to
be court-martialed, tight guard at presidential palace, details on
escape. EDITS to tighten. No pickup.
^LaserPhoto NY74</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The young officer who led an August
coup attempt that nearly felled President Corazon Aquino's
government fled a prison ship in Manila Bay early today aided by
his elite navy guards.
   Mrs. Aquino cut short a private Easter holiday in northern Luzon
and rushed to the capital for an emergency Cabinet meeting after
hearing of the escape of former Lt. Col. Gregorio ``Gringo''
Honasan.
   She told a national television audience Honasan was to have been
court-martialed for leading the bloody Aug. 28 coup attempt, in
which at least 53 people were killed and hundreds wounded.
   Mrs. Aquino warned military personnel that those who assist or
harbor Honasan ``will be dealt with promptly and severely with the
full force of the law.''
   The charismatic soldier escaped at about 2:30 a.m. aboard two
rubber boats along with 14 guards from the navy's Special Warfare
Unit who were guarding him, Col. Oscar Florendo, chief military
spokesman, told reporters.
   Florendo said the roughly half dozen remaining guards fired on
the boats as they slipped away in the darkness, but apparently
missed. The prison ship, the Andres Bonifacio, was anchored 500
yards from the navy's main wharf, he said.
   Chief of Staff Gen. Renato de Villa ordered a nationwide search
for the 39-year-old Honasan, who had been on the ship since his
December arrest in a Manila suburb.
   Armored personnel carriers and bulldozers blocked entrances to
military camps in Manila, and checkpoints were set up on major
highways.
   Florendo said a reserve lieutenant who was frustrated over his
inability to obtain a regular commission had aided in the escape.
   ``It is believed that bribery was a factor,'' the spokesman
added, saying the lieutenant and 13 enlisted personnel had
apparently assisted and joined in the escape. He said the boats
used to flee had been sent to increase security after the military
learned of a plot to free Honasan.
   Florendo warned that Honasan may try to organize a new bid to
topple Mrs. Aquino. He said the government expected Honasan to
resume anti-Aquino propaganda efforts and again try to divide the
military.
   Mrs. Aquino said Honasan fled to avoid prosecution for mutiny
and sedition, arson, murder and conduct unbecoming an officer. She
said his escape ``is tantamount to an admission of his guilt.''
   She also said Honasan staged his coup attempt to evade
investigation of alleged misapproriation of $100,000 worth of
military equipment and to avoid a combat assignment against
communist rebels.
   ``I appeal to all citizens and leaders, public and private, to
assist us in the recapture of Honasan as soon as possible,'' she
said.
   Presidential guards stepped up security around the presidential
palace immediately after word of the escape. Civilians were barred
from the palace compound.
   Defense Secretary Fidel V. Ramos said the military was ``taking
every possible action'' to bring back Honasan and ``minimize or
neutralize any further damage that he can make.''
   Honasan, former Defense Ministry chief of security, played a key
role in the Feb. 22, 1986 mutiny that with a popular uprising
toppled President Ferdinand Marcos.
   But he became disillusioned with Mrs. Aquino, accusing her of
``weak and inept'' leadership that fortified the 19-year-old
communist insurgency.
   On Aug. 28, Honasan led a force of 2,000 men who attacked the
presidential palace and seized several media and military
installations in the capital before they were driven off by
pro-Aquino forces.
   Mrs. Aquino said the attack it was aimed at killing her and her
family.
   Honasan's was the most serious of several major plots to unseat
Mrs. Aquino. The military says 11 officers and 90 enlisted men
involved in the coup attempt are still at large.
   Honasan is widely regarded within the 160,000-member armed
forces as a courageous, experienced officer. Military sources,
speaking on condition of anonymity, said he is so popular he had
become the ``dominant figure'' aboard the ship that was supposed to
be his prison.
   Florendo said the military received information a week ago that
Honasan would try to escape and it sent rubber boats to guard the
ship, expecting outsiders to try to storm the vessel. ``Instead, it
came from the inside.''
   Honasan was Defense Ministry security chief when opposition Sen.
Juan Ponce Enrile was minister of national defense. Enrile was
fired in November 1986 after the government said it thwarted a coup
attempt by his followers.
   Honasan remained in hiding for months after the August coup.
   Maj. Gen. Ramon Montano, former commander of the National
Capital Regional Defense Command, said weeks before the arrest that
Honasan was being protected by undisclosed civilian and military
figures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
