<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 0715EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     04-02 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A disc jockey who told a white lie about
the weather found his listeners ready for an April Fools' Day snow
job.
   WKIR-FM radio personality Dan Baxter told a whopper about the
weather that was swallowed hook, line and sinker by some listeners.
His phony forecast _ freezing rain and snow _ in a state where the
merest hint of winter weather sends residents scurrying to the
grocery put a damper on at least one businessman's day.
   ``They said the rain was supposed to turn to sleet and snow, and
the temperature tonight and tomorrow was going to be in the 20s,''
said barber Larry Kirk, who said trade was slow following Baxter's
bogus prediction of icy streets.
   ``I'm not going to listen to that station any more,'' Kirk said.
   The state Highway Patrol was bombarded with anxious calls about
road conditions. Troopers were stymied, however, when they turned
to the National Weather Service for help.
   ``The weather service called us wanting to know where we got our
information,'' station spokeswoman Rhonda Perry said. ``Then the
Highway Patrol called wanting to talk to the station manager. Then,
the Civil Defense called wanting to talk to the station manager.''
   Baxter went on air to apologize, and told listeners he'd lost
his job.
   April Fool!
   ``He's still kidding around,'' Perry said.
   ``The phone hasn't stopped ringing (with listeners concerned for
Baxter) since I got in,'' said Tim Allen, the disc jockey who
follows Baxter.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A disc jockey's on-air account of an
unidentified flying object causing commotion in a park was so
convincing that some people claimed they witnessed the mysterious
rumble and flash of light.
   ``People are seeing it. But it ain't there,'' said Fred
Honsberger, news director for KDKA-AM, the station that broadcast
the April Fools' Day joke.
   ``We just had a lady call who said she saw a bunch of gray
trucks go in led by a jeep. These people are claiming to have seen
that thing. But we started it all,'' Honsberger said, chuckling.
   Not everyone was laughing.
   Worried listeners flooded the switchboard at the Allegheny
County police station in North Park. Sgt. William Wolverton
repeatedly assured callers there was nothing going on and that the
radio report had been a hoax.
   ``They were pretty much upset with the fact that a radio station
would be allowed to get away it,'' Wolverton said. ``A lot of them
were critical because they picked Good Friday. Good Friday seemed
to be more important than April Fools' Day.''
   Morning disc jockey John Cigna startled his listeners with the
report and offered no explanation or elaboration when he ended his
four-hour broadcast at 9 a.m. But his replacement, Doug Hawkes,
informed listeners it had been a joke.
   ``Remember everyone, today is April Fools' Day,'' Hawkes said.
   None of the morning news reports included the so-called
emergency, Honsberger noted.
   ``That should be a clue to anybody,'' he said. ``If anything was
happening, it would be our lead story. We'd have reporters there.''
</TEXT>
