<2ND_LINE>PM-Texas Tornadoes,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tornadoes Damage Parts Of East Texas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUND CITY, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tornadoes touched down in five east
Texas towns, destroying two mobiles homes, damaging dozens of
houses and overturning cars, authorities said. One minor injury was
reported.
   In East Mountain, near Longview, a tornado damaged 25 homes
Friday, blowing seven or eight of them off their foundations,
witnesses said.
   ``I was on top of the mountain watching for tails out of the
clouds when the rain began falling so hard you couldn't even see,''
said East Mountain Assistant City Marshal Phil Luchau. ``We knew
the storm was getting worse, but it happened so quick, there wasn't
time to warn anyone.''
   A tornado also destroyed two mobile homes and damaged three
homes in nearby Glenwood Acres, officials said, but it was unclear
whether it was the same tornado that struck East Mountain.
   The city hall, an elementary school and a car dealership
suffered heavy damage at Gladewater, about 20 miles northwest of
Longview. A supermarket and several mobile homes also were hit.
   Another tornado damaged four homes in Mound City, and severely
damaged the Mound City Store.
   ``It just hasn't sunk in yet,'' said Deanna Holden, owner of the
store. ``We just all got underneath the dining room table. If we
hadn't gotten my grandbaby out of her crib, she'd be dead because
of all the flying glass.''
   Shan Haggerty, 10, of Houston was cut on the hand by flying
glass as he crouched beneath a kitchen table of a Mound City home
he was visiting.
   A tornado also was spotted in Union Grove, where strong winds
destroyed one home and damaged at least one other.
   At least four tornadoes hit Anderson County in 1987, killing two
people. Three of them hit the southern part of the county, near
Mound City.
   ``This is a bad area for tornadoes,'' said Tommie Denson of
Mound City. ``We're going to move. I'm going to sell my home and
leave.''
</TEXT>
