<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 0815EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Pope-Shultz     04-02 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pope-Shultz,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Gets Pope's Blessing for Mideast Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz today
received Pope John Paul II's blessing on the eve of his new Middle
East peace mission. The pontiff stressed any accord must respect
the ``legitimate rights'' of both Israel and the Palestinians.
   ``God bless your efforts,'' the pope told Shultz following their
30-minute private meeting in the papal library.
   ``I go from here to the Middle East with your blessing to
sustain the effort'' to spur the Arab-Israeli peace process, Shultz
responded in front of reporters and photographers.
   Shultz leaves for Jerusalem on Sunday on the first part of a
trip that will also take him to Jordan, Syria, Egypt and Saudi
Arabia. His trip to the region last month failed to bring an
agreement.
   Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro said the talks focused on the
two mens' ``common preoccupation for international peace,''
specifically East-West relations, ``the continuing grave
situation'' in the Middle East and developments in Central America.
   The pope ``insisted on the legitimate rights of the Palestinian
people and on the moral duty to find a solution that also takes
into account the legitimate rights of Israel,'' the spokesman said.
   John Paul voiced ``great interest in the efforts under way for
the search, obligatory for everyone, of a process that opens the
way to solutions acceptable to all,'' Navarro said.
   The pope has frequently spoken in favor of a Palestinian
homeland.
   The Vatican does not have diplomatic relations with Israel.
Vatican officials have cited the Palestinian question, Israel's
unsettled boundaries and the status of Jerusalem as reasons for the
absence of ties.
   The Vatican does not have diplomatic relations with Jordan
either.
   Shultz, who is Episcopalian, brought to the Vatican today an
entourage of 31 people, including his wife, Helena, a Roman
Catholic.
   After a salute in the Vatican's marbled, frescoed Clementine
room by seven Swiss guards in multi-colored uniforms designed by
Michelangelo, Shultz was ushered into the pope's chambers by
Archbishop Dino Monduzzi, head of the papal household.
   Following the audience, the two were joined by Mrs. Shultz,
wearing a black dress and a black lace mantilla over her head, and
the U.S. ambassador to the Holy See, Frank Shakespeare, and his
21-year-old daughter, Fredericka.
   John Paul, wearing white robes, presented Shultz with a framed
sketch by Italian artist Lello Scorzelli. He gave pontifical medals
and rosaries to the others.
   The group then moved to the Salome Throne Room, where the pope
shook hands with the rest of the delegation, including Secret
Service agents and State Department spokesman Charles Redman. The
pope wished them all a happy Easter.
   It was Shultz's third meeting at the Vatican with John Paul. He
and his wife visited the Vatican in 1986 for Easter. The previous
meeting was in December 1982.
   Shultz and his wife are scheduled to attend the pope's Easter
Mass in St. Peter's Square on Sunday morning.
</TEXT>
