<HEAD>Rain, Snow Fall on Midwest and Tornados Rip Through Texas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, correcting Gove to Grove</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain and snow inundated Arkansas, Kansas, Oklahoma and Colorado
today after tornadoes in five east Texas towns destroyed two mobile
homes and damaged dozens of houses, a city hall, a school and a car
dealership.
   A tornado that touched down in East Mountain did some of the
worst damage of Friday's east Texas twisters, damaging 25 houses,
officials said. Two mobile homes were destroyed in nearby Glenwood
Acres.
   A tornado in Gladewater extensively damaged the city hall, an
elementary school, a car dealership, a supermarket and several
mobile homes, while a funnel cloud that struck near Mound City
damaged a roof and overturned vehicles.
   A tornado was also spotted in Union Grove, where strong
thunderstorm winds destroyed a home and damaged at least one house.
   The only injury reported was to a 10-year-old Mound City boy
whose hand was cut by flying glass.
   As snow piled up in western Kansas, the Oklahoma Panhandle and
eastern Colorado, flooding became more widespread across Arkansas,
Oklahoma and Kansas.
   Blizzard conditions continued late Friday in the Oklahoma
Panhandle. Twenty-two inches of snow fell at Goodwell and 15 inches
at Guymon.
   Clayton, N.M., had 10 inches of snow and drifts up to 6 feet
high. All roads to the city were closed.
   In southeast Colorado, La Junta was blanketed by a foot of snow
in seven hours with 16 inches already on the ground.
   A blizzard warning remained in effect today for western portions
of the Oklahoma Panhandle. Winter storm warnings were issued for
the northern Texas Panhandle and the southeast corner of Colorado.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
southeastern South Dakota to eastern sections of Nebraska and
Kansas, the lower and middle Mississippi Valley, Alabama and the
southern and central Appalachians; scattered thunderstorms over
western Georgia and the Florida Panhandle; scattered rain showers
lingering over eastern Texas and northern Oklahoma; and light snow
from the Texas Panhandle into western Kansas.
   Highs were expected to be in the 60s or 70s in much of the
nation; 40s and 50s from Colorado to northern New Mexico, the Texas
Panhandle, the central Plains, the upper half of the Mississippi
Valley, the Great Lakes and New England; 50s over Washington state;
and 80s over inland Southern California, the desert Southwest,
south Texas and the Florida Panhandle.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 20
degrees at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 75 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 60 partly cloudy; Boston 49 cloudy; Buffalo 36
fair; Charleston, S.C. 60 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 58 rain;
Cleveland 50 foggy; Miami 72 fair; New York 45 cloudy; Philadelphia
49 cloudy; Pittsburgh 51 foggy; Portland, Maine, 38 cloudy;
Washington 52 foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 33 fair; Chicago 44 foggy; Denver 32 cloudy;
Des Moines 45 foggy; Indianapolis 57 foggy; Kansas City 55 rain;
Minneapolis-St. Paul 42 partly cloudy; Nashville 60 cloudy; New
Orleans 69 rain; St. Louis 60 foggy.
   _West: Albuquerque 33 fair; Anchorage 34 cloudy; Las Vegas 51
fair; Phoenix 60 fair; Salt Lake City 35 fair; San Francisco 47
fair; Seattle 47 foggy.
   _Canada: Montreal 37 fair; Toronto 34 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
