<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Journal-Pulitzer,0144</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Donating Prize Money To Infant Mortality Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Alabama Journal, which won a 1988
Pulitzer Prize for a series about the state's infant mortality
problem, is donating its prize money to help fight the stituation.
   Richard Amberg said the newspaper will donate the $3,000 prize
to the Gift of Life Foundation, a Montgomery group dedicated to
lowering the state's infant mortality rate, which is the highest of
any state.
   In addition, the newspaper's parent company, Multimedia, will
match the $3,000 donation, Amberg said Friday.
   ``We want to demonstrate our personal commitment to this problem
by donating this money,'' the publisher said.
   The newspaper won a Pulitzer Prize for general news reporting
for a series on why more than 13 out of every 1,000 babies born in
Alabama die before their first birthday.
</TEXT>
