<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iraq-Kurds 1stLd-Writethru a0489 04-02 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iraq-Kurds, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0489,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kurdistan War Escalates As Iraq Claims Guerrilla Bases Overrun</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 8 grafs to CORRECT spelling of Qara Dagh and
update with guerrilla leader confirming heavy fighting. Picks up
7th pvs, `He said...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said today that its forces have
overrun Kurdish guerrilla bases in the mountainous northeast in an
offensive aimed at crushing Iranian-backed rebels who threaten
vital oilfields.
   Kurdish guerrilla leaders have claimed the Iraqis, backed by
tanks and air strikes, were dropping poison gas bombs on villages
in what one commander called ``a war of genocide.''
   Baghdad Radio, monitored in Nicosia, quoted a military
communique as saying its troops ``completely purged'' the area
around Qara Dagh in the Sulaimaniyeh region, 50 miles west of the
Kirkuk oilfields.
   Qara Dagh is only 20 miles west of Lake Darbandikhan, where
Iranian Revolutionary Guards have thrust into Iraq in a 16-day-old
offensive.
   ``All traitors have finally been destroyed,'' the communique
declared in a reference to the Iranian-backed Kurdish rebels who
have been fighting Baghdad for an independent homeland for years.
   There was no independent confirmation.
   Jalal Talabani, leader of the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan, told
The Associated Press that heavy fighting was raging in the region
Friday but that he had no reports of an Iraqi breakthrough.
   Massud Barzani, leader of the Iranian-backed Kurdish Democratic
Party, said in a statement several days ago, that the Iraqi army
had launched a major offensive against the guerrillas March 23.
   He said two divisions of troops, backed by tanks, artillery and
air strikes, were seeking to dislodge Kurdish fighters from the
Qara Dagh mountains between Kirkuk and the provincial capital of
Sulaimaniyeh.
   An Iraqi division usually numbers about 12,000 men.
   Barzani said the Iraqi assaults had been beaten back.
   He claimed Iraqi warplanes were dropping chemical bombs on
Kurdish strongholds and villages suspected of harboring guerrillas.
   The villages were north of the Iranian bridgehead around Lake
Darbandikhan, where Iran claims Iraqi chemical bombing attacks
March 16-17 killed 5,000 civilians and injured as many more.
   Talabani said the Iraqis had seized some villages. He also
charged the Iraqi air force was dropping gas bombs on Kurdish
settlements.
   ``It's a war of genocide against the Kurdish people,'' he said
in a telephone interview. ``They use chemical weapons against us
all the time and raze our villages.''
   Today's communique said an Iraqi force, including Kurdish
fighters loyal to Baghdad, had overrun 21 Kurdish bases and
villages used by the guerrillas in the last few days. It gave no
casualty figure.
   The Kurdish guerrillas have in the last 18 months created a
second front in the 7{-year-old Iran-Iraq war. The Iraqis have had
to divert tens of thousands of troops badly needed in the main
battle zones in the south to contain the insurgency in Kurdistan.
   The Kurds claimed to control 4,000 square miles in the northeast.
   About 20 million Kurds live in the mountainous region where the
borders of Iran, Iraq, Syria and Turkey meet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880402-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 1111EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Drugs     04-02 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Drugs,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guangdong Authorities Reportedly Smash Drug Ring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities in the southern Chinese province of
Guangdong seized 792 pounds of opium and heroin and arrested
several gangsters involved in drug smuggling, the pro-Beijing
newspaper Wen Wei Po reported Saturday.
   The newpaper did not say how many people were arrested but said
the gang had more than 80 members who have been dealing in drugs
since 1985.
   It said the gang transported the drugs from the Golden Triangle
area of Vietnam, Burma and Thailand to the southern Chinese
province of Yunnan and Guangdong and then to the British colony of
Hong Kong.
   The operation was directed by a Hong Kong man identified only as
Chan X Kwong, the newspaper said, but it did not say if Chan was
among those arrested.
   It said Chan directed the drug smuggling operation with a walkie
talkie from a house in suburban Canton, the capital of Guangdong
province.
   A truck modified in Hong Kong transported 264 pounds of the
drugs through the Chinese Special Economic Zone of Shenzhen into
neighboring Hong Kong, the paper said.
   The gang members fought among themselves and Chan reportedly
tried to rob his partner Ah Wing last year, the paper said.
   Hong Kong police said they have not heard of the gang.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
