<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 1111EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mozambique     04-02 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mozambique,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Huge Price Hikes Take Effect; Government Troops Kill 38 Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Marxist government imposed huge
price inceases on food, and a government newspaper said Saturday
that the increases were necessitated by a guerrilla war that has
ravaged the economy.
   Prices for rice, sugar, corn, cooking oil, bread and soap all
rose sharply under government-mandated increases that took effect
Friday in the southern African nation. In a bid to offset the
higher food prices, the government also granted wage increases to
some workers.
   Rice went from 9 cents to 60 cents per kilogram, about 2.2
pounds. Corn flour rose from nine cents to 32 cents per kilogram
and a kilogram of sugar went from 11 cents to 59 cents.
   The minimum wage for an industrial worker has been raised from
about $17 a month to $29 per month. However, raises were not
granted to workers in factories that were losing money.
   Mozambique also has a high unemployment rate and thousands of
refugees displaced by a war raging since the 1960s. Mozambique won
independence from Portugal in 1975 after years of fighting. Since
then guerrillas of the Mozambique National Resistance have been
battling to oust the Marxist government.
   The daily newspaper Noticias, in an editorial Saturday, blamed
the country's economic woes on ``the continued and systematic
aggression against Mozambique, carried out by the racist regimes of
the region _ first Rhodesia and later South Africa.''
   In the mid-1970s, then white-ruled Rhodesia helped backed the
anti-Marxist guerrillas. After Rhodesia became black-ruled Zimbabwe
in 1980, South Africa began supplying the rebels.
   South Africa and Mozambique signed a mutual non-aggression pact
in 1984, but both sides regularly accuse the other of violations.
   Noticias said foreign support of the rebels has destabilized
Mozambique and ``has prevented us from consolidating our
independence and developing our economy.''
   ``Mozambique, devastated by more than 20 consecutive years of
war, is currently one of the poorest countries in the world,''
Noticias said. ``The state can no longer go on paying food
subsidies.''
   An estimated 5 million of Mozambique's 14.5 million people are
in need of food aid.
   In other developments, government troops killed 38 rebel
fighters in clashes during the past week in three separate
provinces, the national news agency AIM said.
   The rebels were killed in clashes from March 29-31 in the
central provinces of Sofala and Zambazia and the northwestern
province of Tete, AIM said, citing a report on Radio Mozambique.
   The report made no mention of government troop casualties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
