<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-FaureFuneral     04-02 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Faure Funeral,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Leads Mourners At Funeral Of Edgar Faure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Francois Mitterrand and politicians from
France's left and right put aside their quarrels Saturday and paid
their last respects to Edgar Faure, one of the most widely
respected statesmen of the century.
   Faure, a brilliant and witty politician who in four decades of
service occupied nearly every important French government post
except president, died Wednesday at the age of 79.
   The ceremony at Paris' St. Clotilde Basilica was simple. Faure's
plain coffin was draped with the French Tricolor. Upon it was
placed the bicorn hat and sword of the Academie Francaise, of which
he was a member.
   Mgr. Daniel Pezeril, former auxiliary bishop of Paris,
represented Cardinal Jean-Marie Lustiger in conducting the service.
In his brief homily, Pezeril noted Faure's long fight for human
rights, saying he believed such a fight was a ``touchstone of
political responsibility.''
   ``As a Christian, the deceased will have thus participated in
the fate of the world,'' he said.
   Also attending were Bernadette Chirac, representing her husband,
Premier Jacques Chirac, who was on a trip to the French Antilles;
former President Valery Giscard d'Estaing; Jacques Chaban-Delmas,
president of the National Assembly; Alain Poher, president of the
Senate; Finance Minister Edouard Balladur and other present and
former leaders and opposition members.
   Faure was known for his oratorial skills and his ability to
advance policies that went beyond the traditional right-left
cleavage in French politics.
   Although he was a member of several Socialist governments in the
Fourth Republic, he was widely respected by all.
   His last post was as head of the bicentennial commemoration of
the French Revolution, which occurs next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
