<DOCNO> AP880402-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 1114EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Trade Bjt   04-02 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade, Bjt,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Bucks for Corn and Bean Research Snag Trade Measure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Efforts to wrap up farm provisions of the
1,000-page trade bill are snagged over a plan by Sen. Tom Harkin,
D-Iowa, to pump $75 million a year into crop research every year
for 20 years.
   The plan is designed principally to spur demand for corn and
soybeans by finding new, non-food uses for them, leading to higher
farm earnings. ``It's really a long-term agricultural bill, an
investment in the future,'' press secretary Pam McKinney says.
   Thus far, House negotiators on the trade bill aren't so sure.
   The plan would be a boon for Iowa State University and similar
research centers but could whet other lawmakers' appetites for more
of the same for the folks back in their own states.
   The chairman of the House Agriculture Committee, E. ``Kika'' de
la Garza, D-Texas, has been cool toward the notion thus far. And
for that reason farm lawmakers were still wrangling late in the
week, when most other conferees on the trade bill had reached
tentative agreement.
   It now appears unlikely that the matter will be resolved until
after April 11, when Congress returns from its spring break.
   As big as it is, the plant research provision is small potatoes
compared to some of the subsidy programs that do have tentative
approval from the trade conferees.
   Chief among them is a so-called ``triggered marketing loan''
program, similar to export subsidies contained in the 1985 farm
law, that sent U.S. cotton and rice exports skyrocketing _ but at a
hefty price to taxpayers.
   The latest proposal focuses on the Reagan administration's goal
of using the current Uruguay Round of trade talks to start the
United States and its trading partners on a course of phasing out
all agricultural subsidies.
   Failure to make ``substantial progress'' on such an agreement by
1990 would trigger the estimated $500 million marketing loan
program designed to boost exports of wheat, feed grains and oilseed
crops.
   Soybean farmers have been clamoring for a marketing loan
program, under which producers receive price-support loans from the
government as usual, pay them off at the lower, world price of the
crop and pocket the difference.
   Even if Uruguay Round talks bogged down, the next president
could refuse to put the 1990 marketing loan into effect if he were
prepared to assure Congress that the subsidy program would would
harm the international negotiations.
   Doing that, however, would trigger one of the trade package's
most expensive and complex features _ an offshoot of the 1985
Export Enhancement Program, which has sent millions of dollars in
government-owned surplus crops to private exporters.
   Big grain companies and other exporting firms receive the
surplus crops as bonuses to spur overseas shipments of American
farm products.
   The program remains in effect and the trade proposal would
extend it through 1990 and boost the price tag from $1.5 billion to
$2.5 billion.
   A presidential waiver of the marketing loan would automatically
trigger a new export program, requiring the government to pay out
no less than $2 billion in additional surplus-crop bonuses. These
bonuses represent a heavy cost to taxpayers because the commodities
were acquired mainly through unredeemed price-support loans to
farmers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
