<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TimeChanges     04-02 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Time Changes,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Time Change Means More Than Lost Hour Of Sleep</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH HARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the clock jumps forward an hour for
daylight-saving time at 2 a.m. Sunday morning, it means a little
more than a lost hour of sleep.
   ``People's stomachs will be telling them `Snickers bar' and
we'll be serving lunch. But if you're an early eater, it'll be
beneficial,'' said Jeff Manzer, manager of the Chattanooga
Riverboat Company.
   The firm plans to serve an Easter brunch on the Tennessee river
Sunday afternoon, but the time change ``will probably affect
people's appetites,'' said Manzer.
   Businesses and services that work on into the night lost an hour
_ or gained an hour, depending on the point of view.
   Some police officers who work the night shift get to go home an
hour early. They don't lose an hour's pay for their ``early''
departure. And when the time changes back in the fall, they'll get
an hour's overtime pay, officials said Friday.
   Firefighters who work 24-hour shifts are in the same situation.
   Some churches will hold additional services for sleepyheads and
for the holiday crowds.
   Going visiting for Easter? The nation's public transportation
system is ready for the switch, said Fred Waymack, manager of a
Nashville travel agency.
   ``At some points there are some minor changes in schedules, but
for most airlines, cruise ships and trains, it's just another day
on the job,'' Waymack said.
   Most of the schedule changes come about because of the season,
not daylight-saving time, he said. Some flight times might be
adjusted one or two minutes because of changes in headwinds,
Waymack said, and others might be changed to accommodate peak
passenger loads.
   ``It's really a very sophisticated system,'' Waymack said.
``They've had a number of years since the Wright brothers to
perfect it.''
   But he urged passengers to double-check departures 24 hours in
advance.
   At First Tennessee Bank in Memphis, spokesman Bob Young said the
time change would have little effect on most banking services.
However, he said, there might be a moment's hesitation when
computer operators key in the commands to switch times on the
banking computers, automated tellers and other equipment.
   ``It just depends on how quickly an operator can enter it in,''
Young said.
   Recorded time and temperature announcements must be changed,
along with signs at banks, shopping malls and stores. Teresa
Birdsong, assistant to the general manager at Nashville's WYHY-FM,
said she will have to come to the station at 2 a.m. Sunday morning
to make the change in the time and temperature announcement
computer.
   Bank and store signs are also changed by computer, usually by
the owner of the sign, said Mark Allison, owner of Allison Sales
and Marketing.
   ``The time works off an internal clock, which you reset just as
you would a digital clock,'' Allison said.
   Time clocks must also be changed before workers punch in Monday
morning. Most computerized time clocks will make the change
automatically, but there will still be thousands of older models
that need to be changed by hand, said Southern Time Services
technician Bill Asplint.
   ``We could be doing daylight-saving time changes for the next
two weeks,'' he said.
   This is the second year that daylight-saving time will begin on
the first Sunday in April. Before Congress changed the law, the
time switch occurred on the last Sunday of April.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880402-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 1127EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Armenia     04-02 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official, Dissident Sources Say Ethnic Situation Quieter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikes, demonstrations and tensions between
national groups in two southern Soviet republics have quieted but
economic damage from the unrest is severe, newspapers reported
Saturday.
   Official and dissident sources said the atmosphere in the
republics of Armenia and Azerbaijan was improving. But in Moscow,
activist Sergei Grigoryants said ethnic relations remained volatile.
   At a news conference at his north Moscow apartment, the
half-Armenian former political prisoner said he had spoken with
sources in Armenia who told him tensions have eased there and in
the disputed region of Nagorno-Karabakh in neighboring Azerbaijan.
   However, he said he was told some residents of Stepanakert,
Nagorno-Karabakh's main city, remained on strike.
   Armenian activists want Nagorno-Karabakh, which is mostly
Armenian, annexed to Armenia. At least 32 people have died in
ethnic violence in the region since late February in bloody clashes
between Azeris and Armenians.
   Grigoryants said the Stepanakert airport had been reopened for
local residents but that frequent document checks were being made
at all roads leading into the region to keep outsiders away.
   Workers in Stepanakert, angered over the Kremlin's failure to
issue a clear decision on appeals to annex the region, have been
staying home for more than a week.
   Official newspapers acknowledged labor unrest continued, but
said more people have been showing up for work. In the beginning,
virtually the entire adult population went out on strike.
   The Communist Party newspaper Pravda carried an interview with
Armenian scholar Gevorg Garibdzhanyan, who accused the state-run
press of telling a one-sided story about the Nagorno-Karabakh
situation and being too quick to label Armenian activists as
extremists.
   But he also defended the presence of Soviet troops in the
Armenian capital of Yerevan, saying he ``slept peacefully knowing
our soldiers were in the city.''
   It appeared from his comments that the armed security troops
that patrolled the city last month had been reduced.
   Foreign reporters have been barred from traveling to the
Caucasus region and telephone contact with the area has been
disrupted.
   The national television news program Vremya reported Friday that
public transport and many major industries in Stepanakert had been
idled by the strikes and urged residents of the area to go back to
work.
   The daily Sovietskaya Rossiya said Saturday that some workers
showed up at major enterprises in the city of Stepanakert on Friday
for the first time in more than a week, although the factories were
still not up to full strength.
   An editor who answered the telephone at the Soviet Karabakh
newspaper in Stepanakert on Saturday said the labor situation was
returning to normal in the city, but declined to give his name or
details.
   Selskaya Zhizn newspaper wrote that state and collective farms
in the troubled region had lost nearly $775,000 by mid-March
because of strikes and demonstrations. Shortages of meat, milk and
eggs have resulted, the newspaper said.
   Even larger losses have been reported in recent days due to the
industrial strikes in Stepanakert, where production and deliveries
ground to a halt over the past week.
   Nagorno-Karabakh has been part of the Azerbaijan republic since
1923, although more than three-quarters of the region's 160,000
residents are Armenians. Armenians are predominantly Christian,
while most Azeris are Shiite Moslems.
   The labor situation worsened in Stepanakert in mid-March, when
the Soviet leadership called Armenian agitation for
Nagorno-Karabakh's annexation ``intolerable.''
   While apparently rejecting the bid for reuniting the region with
Armenia, the party and government leadership unveiled a program to
invest $690 million in housing and social services like
Armenian-language schools, literature and broadcasting.
</TEXT>
