<DOCNO> AP880402-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 1131EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Shultz     04-02 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Calls Again For Ouster Of Noriega's Ouster</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz insisted
Saturday on the ouster of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega but
sidestepped a report that he had recommended kidnapping the
Panamanian strongman.
   Shultz predicted he would ``see a little headway'' when he again
takes up his plan for Mideast peace talks next week with Arab and
Israeli leaders. Shultz called on Palestinians to participate in
the negotiations, but he again ruled out talks with the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   ``Obviously, there are some we won't meet with,'' Shultz said as
he reiterated the 13-year-old U.S. policy of not dealing with the
PLO until it accepts Irael's right to exist.
   Shultz held the news conference after receiving Pope John Paul
II's blessing at the Vatican for his new venture in the Middle East
that begins Sunday evening in Jerusalem. The pope stressed any
accord must respect the ``legitimate rights'' of both Israelis and
Palestinians.
   The Vatican does not have diplomatic relations with Israel nor
does it recognize its control of once-divided Jerusalem, the
Israeli capital.
   The Los Angeles Times reported Friday that Shultz recommended
kidnapping Noriega and fomenting a military coup coordinated with
the Central Intelligence Agency.
   The newspaper also said Shultz and Elliott Abrams, the assistant
secretary of state for Inter-American affairs, suggested landing
more than 3,000 U.S. soldiers to encourage Panamanian military
officers to move against Noriega.
   The proposal was strongly opposed by the CIA and Defense
Secretary Frank C. Carlucci, who labeled it dangerous and
ill-timed, said the Times, quoting unidentified adniminstration
officials.
   Asked if he made such recommendations, Shultz said ``the
position of the U.S. government is that Noriega should go.
Everybody agrees about that. He's been indicted on drug charges.''
   In a lengthy reply, Shultz said the Panamanian people have
demonstrated they agree with the United States in opposing Noriega.
He said U.S. forces in Panama were being increased to guard the
Panama Canal.
   ``We debate various possible options,'' Shultz said. ``But
basically this is a question of a person who is no longer welcome
in his own country by his own people and he should leave.''
   When another reporter suggested Shultz had not really answered
the question, Shultz showed some irritation and said, ``I never
comment on speculative newspaper articles.''
   Told U.S. officials reportedly had described a kidnapping plot
as harebrained, Shultz said: ``I never comment on particularly
harebrained-type proposals.''
   He also refused to say whether the United States would seek
Noriega's extradition to face criminal charges.
   Shultz and his wife, Helena, are spending a leisurely weekend in
the Italian capital and planned to attend the Pope's Easter Mass in
St. Peter's Square.
   Shultz also held a series of meetings with Italian government
officials.
   He praised Italy for its willingness to host the 72 U.S. F-16
jet fighter planes that Spain is expelling in 1991.
   On the Middle East, Shultz said he had no further word from
Arabs and Israelis on whether they would accept his proposal, but
``we expect to see a little headway.''
   His plan calls for negotiations to begin May 1 on arrangements
for self-rule for the 1.5 million Palestinians on the Israeli-held
West Bank and in Gaza.
   Israel would deal directly with a joint delegation of Jordan and
Palestinians. In December, negotiations on an overall settlement of
the 40-year Arab-Israeli dispute would open, also with Syria's
participation.
   Shultz said he would keep working for peace even if he were
turned down on his second trip to the region in a month.
   ``The problem is there,'' he said. ``Everybody recognizes it.
And the problem isn't going to go away.''
   Shultz said after talking with Arab and Israeli leaders he could
``feel it in my bones there is an answer out there if you can only
find it.''
</TEXT>
