<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     04-02 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roland Dickey once again is ready to don a
rabbit costume and take some holiday cheer to area hospitals in his
annual spring role as the ``ether bunny.''
   Dickey, 73, first put on the fuzzy suit and long ears when
fellow members of the Loyal Order of Moose asked him to preside
over the club's annual Easter egg hunt.
   ``Then I got the idea that I would like to expand and bring the
bunny into the children's hospital wards,'' Dickey said. Nurses
dubbed him the ``ether bunny'' many years ago after he fainted on
the bunny trail, he said.
   ``I was at Methodist Hospital, walking back to the children's
wards, when I walked past one of the operating rooms,'' Dickey
said. ``Back in those days, they used ether as anesthetic. The
ether got trapped up in that bunny head and out I went.''
   After doing his routine for 41 years, Dickey said he has no
plans to retire.
   ``Everybody asks me, `When are you going to get someone else to
do it?' I want to keep doing it for as long as I can,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Wolf wasn't taking calls at the Bronx Zoo
Friday.
   Neither did Buffy Lowe, Bob Katz, Bob Boon, Don Key or P.N.
Gwynne. But that didn't stop many April Fools' targets from trying
to return calls to those characters.
   ``They's groaners, I'm telling you,'' Luanne McGrain, a
publicist for the zoo, said Friday. ``We've had a lot of doctors
calling _ `This is Dr. Rosenberg. May I speak to Mr. G. Raffe?'''
   For the second year running, the zoo turned the annual prank
into a brief fund-raiser. Other zoos around the nation use the same
tactics with people are fooled into calling on April Fools' Day.
   The switchboard answered calls Friday with ``NYZS,'' the call
letters of the New York Zoological Society. When callers said they
were returning a call from Mr. Wolf, they were transferred to a
volunteer phone bank.
   ``They say, `Mr. Wolf is being fed right now. You have reached
the Bronx Zoo. Somebody's played a joke on you for April Fools'
Day. But while I have you on the phone, would you care to make a
donation?''' McGrain said.
   ``If they can stop laughing long enough, generally people do
make a pledge.''
   Callers wound up making $4,000 in donations, which New York
Telephone has promised to match.
</TEXT>
