<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Italy-Locusts     04-02 0155</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Italy-Locusts,0158</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dead Locusts Littering Beaches Near Rome</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of dead African desert locusts have shown
up on beaches just outside Rome, the Coast Guard reported Saturday,
prompting concerns some swarms might reach Italy alive.
   Coast Guard officials said winds must have pushed the insects
from Northern Africa toward Italy and that they died in the cold
weather.
   The Italian press expressed concern that warmer weather might
allow future swarms of locusts to survive and thrive. The Rome
daily Il Tempo described the scene on the beach as ``the sign of a
narrowly missed invasion, or worse, of an invasion that lies at the
gates.''
   But experts have said Italy will not be hit by the same invasion
of locusts that has spread over Morocco, Tunisia, Algeria and
Libya. Last month, the Rome-based U.N. Food and Agriculture
Organization described the insect invasion in North Africa as the
worst in 30 years.
</TEXT>
