<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880402-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 1133EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Reagan 1stLd-Writethru a0417 04-02 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0417,000</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan, On Vacation, Keeps Eye on Panama</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 6 grafs with Reagan's spokesman minimizing
possibility of military offensive to oust Noriega; edits 4th and
5th grafs pvs to conform and picks up 6th graf pvs, But the</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration has
considered a number of military alternatives to oust Panamanian
strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega, but has rejected them, President
Reagan's chief spokesman said today.
   Asked about a flurry of news reports that Secretary of State
George P. Shultz was pushing a bold military or covert move to get
Noreiga out, Fitzwater said the Panamanian problem has presented
``fertile ground for a rich imagination'' about possible solutions.
   ``But the United States' intentions are to protect our citizens
and our assets there,'' he said.
   ``There have been any number of offensive plans raised, but to
this point, they have been rejected,'' he added.
   Reagan, who has started a 10-day Easter vacation at his
mountaintop ranch near here, is closely watching the situation,
Fitzwater said, as the Pentagon prepares to send 1,300 U.S.
military personnel to strengthen the American military presence
there.
   Shortly after Reagan arrived in California Friday, the Defense
Department announced that the additional troops would be deployed,
beginning next week, to improve the security of U.S. military
installations in the troubled country.
   The Reagan administration for weeks has been applying economic
and diplomatic pressure to force Noriega out of power. Noriega has
been indicted by a federal grand jury in the United States on drug
trafficking charges.
   Fitzwater, asked earlier this week if the administration was
considering seizing Noriega, said, ``No.''
   But the spokesman told reporters accompanying Reagan to
California on Air Force One on Friday that the administration was
still ``reviewing options'' aimed at securing Noriegan's departure.
   The Pentagon decision to send additional manpower, many of them
military police officers, came in the wake of a march by Panamanian
troops on a Panama City hotel earlier in the week. During that
incident, several U.S. journalists were detained briefly, and
authorities confiscated videotapes of four U.S. television networks.
   Fitzwater said Reagan would be kept abreast of several matters
while the president and his wife, Nancy, relax at Rancho del Cielo
in the Santa Ynez Mountains.
   ``He'll get daily intelligence updates on world situations,''
the spokesman said. ``He could get special information on three or
four areas of interest. One is Panama, a continuing problem to keep
an eye on.''
   Reagan also will be kept informed of any progress that Shultz
makes as he renews the administration's Middle East peacemaking
efforts with visits to several countries in the region.
   The president also will be briefed on the goings-on in
Nicaragua, where the Marxist Sandinista regime is scheduled to
enter talks with the Contra rebels Tuesday aimed at bringing about
democratic reforms envisioned in a truce agreement signed March 23.
   But the political and governmental crisis in Panama seemed sure
to take much of Reagan's attention.
   Reagan has sought to minimize the possibility of U.S. military
force being used to oust Noriega. Last Monday, for instance, he
told high school students in Vienna, Va., he did not think the
citizens of Panama wanted to see ``the great colossus of the
North'' flex its muscles there.
   But the administration apparently has become increasingly
frustrated as Noriega has survived an array of economic sanctions.
These include the withholding of payments the United States makes
to the Panama Canal Commission under terms of the 1979 treaties
providing for the canal to be gradually turned over to Panama by
the turn of the century.
   In another effort to turn the financial screws on Noriega, the
administration on Thursday announced steps to stop U.S. dollars
from flowing into the Central American nation.
   The administration is concerned that the continuing flow of tax
payments by American corporations with operations in Panama has
served to sustain the existing government headed by Noriega.
   The first family plans a quiet Easter vacation, which lasts
through April 10. Fitzwater said there were no plans for
get-togethers at the ranch by Reagan relatives, and it could not be
learned whether the first couple would leave the mountain to attend
Easter services here _ as they did last year.
   Reagan's lone public outing is an appearance Monday at a
luncheon of some 75 supporters of the Reagan presidential library.
   He is scheduled to make a foreign policy address to a convention
of the National Association of Broadcasters in Las Vegas, Nev., en
route back to Washington on April 10.
</TEXT>
