<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MormonConference     04-02 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mormon Conference,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Leaders Preach Love Of God, Divinity Of Jesus</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Embargoed until noon EST</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mormon Church leaders today urged
followers to love God above worldly success and prepare themselves
for the second coming of Jesus Christ.
   In the opening session of the 158th Annual General Conference of
The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, leaders said
service to God and love of Christ should be the highest priority of
the faithful.
   ``We should put God ahead of everyone else in our lives,'' said
President Ezra Taft Benson, the 88-year-old spiritual leader of the
6.5 million member church.
   ``When we put God first, all other things fall into their proper
places or drop out of our lives. Our love of God will govern the
claims for our affection, the demands on our time, the interests we
pursue and the order of our priorities,'' Benson said in prepared
remarks.
   The sermon was the first of three scheduled to be delivered by
Benson, who has been convalescing from a heart attack the past six
months. Church spokesman Jerry Cahill said Benson, who served as
secretary of agriculture during the Eisenhower administration,
appeared to be in good health and excellent spirits.
   Benson was one of 22 of the church's general authorities
scheduled to speak during the conference's five sessions. General
authorities are full-time clergy who lead the church under the
direction of the First Presidency, which consists of Benson and
counselors Gordon B. Hinckley and Thomas S. Monson.
   Thousands of lay clergymen and other church members from around
the world have gathered for the two-day conference held in the
Tabernacle on Temple Square in downtown Salt Lake City.
   During this morning's opening session, leaders stressed
fundamental church doctrines, such as belief in resurrection and
atonement of Jesus and the importance of missionary work.
   Leaders were expected to announce this afternoon that convert
baptisms reached an all-time high during 1987. Cahill said the
exact figure would not be released prior to the afternoon session,
but said it was about 250,000. He said the church's full-time,
volunteer missionary force also has reached an all-time high of
34,200 men and women.
   Neal A. Maxwell, of the Council of the Twelve Apostles, urged
church members to prepare for Christ's second coming, but said they
should not believe the rapture necessarily is near at hand.
   The Council of the Twelve are second to the First Presidency in
the church hierarchy, and assist in directing the church.
   ``Over the sweep of Christian history, by focusing on a few
prophecies while neglecting others, some believers have prematurely
expected the second coming. Today, while obviously closer to that
great moment, we are in the same danger,'' Maxwell said. ``On the
other hand, smugness is also a real danger.''
   Maxwell noted that a number of Biblical prophecies said to be
precursors of Christ's return already have occurred. Among them, he
said, is the return of the Jewish people to the Holy Land.
   L. Tom Perry, of the Council of the Twelve, said Mormons should
get involved in community affairs and promote honest government,
neighborhood beautification and high educational standards.
   ``Rather than spend time complaining about the direction in
which these institutions are going, we need to exert our influence
in shaping the right direction. A small effort by a few can result
in so much good for all mankind,'' he said.
</TEXT>
