<1ST_LINE>u a PM-OhioRiverSpill 1stLd-Writethru a0517 04-02 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ohio River Spill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0517,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Investigating 70-Mile Long Spill On Ohio River</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout, spill 70 miles long; retransmits a0528 to fix
cycle designator</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An apparent fuel spill stretched about 70
miles down the Ohio River today from near Cincinnati to Louisville,
Ky., according to the U.S. Coast Guard.
   ``At this point it smells like diesel fuel, so we are assuming
it is diesel fuel,'' said Lt. Eric Mosher, with the Coast Guard in
Louisville.
   Mosher said his agency had contacted water companies along the
river and health officials in Louisville.
   ``Our first step is trying to find a source and secure the
source,'' Mosher said.
   ``There is about a 1-foot chop on the river right now. To
contain the oil is almost an impossibility,'' he added.
   Sgt. James Hickerson with the Indiana State Police post in
Sellersburg said investigators had used a helicopter this morning
to track the spill about 70 miles.
   ``It's not thick and heavy all the way, but there are traces of
it. It's heaviest between Madison (in Jefferson County) and Clark
County (across the river from Louisville),'' he said.
   ``We don't know exactly what it is, some kind of petroleum,'' he
said.
   ``One report I got from the (police) radio was that it was in
spots as wide as the river. They say it is a real thin film, but
they don't know if it is a fuel or a chemical,'' said patrolman Tim
Armstrong of the police department in Madison, about halfway
between Cincinnati and Louisville.
   Armstrong said Madison residents began reporting a strong diesel
fuel smell Friday night. He said officials at the Indiana-Kentucky
Electric Corp. generating plant took a boat out to check the river
and discovered the spill shortly after 6:30 a.m.
</TEXT>
