<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mecham-MoffordAd     04-02 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham-Mofford Ad,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Telephone Company Selects Acting Governor For Arizona Ad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DAVENPORT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A telephone company has decided to print a
photo of acting Gov. Rose Mofford instead of impeached Gov. Evan
Mecham in an advertisment for Arizona, a spokesman says.
   US West, parent company of Mountain Bell, has been running a
series of full-page ads in the Wall Street Journal highlighting
each of the 14 states in its territory.
   Each ad in the series, which cost $1.4 million and started in
January, includes a picture of the portrayed state's governor and
text provided by the governor. The ads are intended to emphasize
the states' strong points and to encourage business development in
the company's service area.
   The Arizona ad was slated to run early in the series, which
began in January, but was delayed because of circumstances
surrounding Mecham, company officials said in February.
   The state Senate is winding up Mecham's impeachment trial, with
closing arguments scheduled Monday. The first-term Republican also
faces an April 21 criminal trial and a May 17 recall election.
   As secretary of state, Mrs. Mofford, a Democrat, became acting
governor after Mecham was impeached by the Arizona House on Feb. 5.
   Now, US West has decided to go ahead with the Arizona ad the
week of April 18, but with a photo of Mrs. Mofford instead of
Mecham, Mountain Bell spokesman Jim Cullison said Friday.
   ``We certainly don't want to offend anyone or step on any toes.
We just went with what will be the reality at that point, which is
that Rose Mofford will be acting governor at that time,'' said
Cullison.
</TEXT>
