<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Reagan-Radio     04-02 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Radio,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Urges Support for Scientific Research</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan today urged
Congress to enhance federal support of scientific research, saying
``we couldn't be where we are'' without such exploration.
   In his weekly radio address, delivered from Reagan's ranch in
the Santa Ynez Mountains, the president said that while spending
for scientific research is 58 percent higher than a decade ago,
after discounting for inflation, this is insufficient.
   He said that since World War II, the United States has won more
Nobel Prizes for science than Europe and Japan combined, and that
this country must not lose its world leadership role.
   He said that scientific research, unlike the construction of
bridges, interstate highways and courthouses, has no local
constituency. But Reagan said the United States cannot let this
political fact of life get in the way of continuing breakthroughs.
   Without such exploration, ``we couldn't be where we are today,''
he said. ``We can travel as far as the eye of our imagination can
see.''
</TEXT>
