<HEAD>Seattle Judge Releases Suspected Car Thief, Loses Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge who released an 18-year-old suspected car
thief will be seeing the man in court again. This time, the young
man is accused of stealing the judge's car.
   Seattle District Court Judge Philip Y. Killien ruled there was
no compelling reason to hold the teen-ager after he was arrested
for investigation of driving a stolen car.
   The judge decided to release the man, although he had no job and
no permanent address, while police and prosecutors investigated.
The judge's own car was stolen soon afterward.
   Killien said he thought the theft of his car March 22 was
nothing more than a coincidence. He got his car back four days
later.
   Killien was expected to testify against the suspect, who is
charged in two other cases but has not not yet charged in the
judge's case.
   The man is back in King County Jail.
