<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Burma-Drugs     04-02 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Burma-Drugs,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burma Paper Denies Government Deals Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state-owned newspaper denied rebel
charges that Burmese government authorities carry out large-scale
drug trafficking.
   Kachin rebel leader Brang Seng last month told foreign
correspondents that his forces overran a military outpost in
Burma's northern Kachin state. He said they captured 180 boxes
filled with 5,016 pounds of opium, which he cited as evidence of
government involvement in drug dealing.
   But the Burmese state-owned Working People's Daily said in its
report, published Wednesday and made available Saturday in Bangkok,
that the rebels found drugs stored for use as court evidence.
   The article went on to accuse the Kachin rebels, one of several
minority groups fighting the central government, of smuggling jade,
heroin and opium to bankroll their activities.
   Burma is the world's largest producer of opium with an
anticipated harvest this season of up to 1,200 tons, officials say.
