<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 1259EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Sikhs 1stLd-Writethru a0539 04-02 0834</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Sikhs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0539,0856</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Compromise Appears Unlikely After Punjab's Bloodiest Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with new deaths reported. Picks
up 5th graf, `No new...</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With 23 more deaths reported Saturday,
India's troubled state of Punjab has suffered the bloodiest week
since Sikh rebels first began calling for a separate nation six
years ago.
   Last week's death toll of 120 has prompted calls for imposing a
federal emergency in the northern state and already may have
crippled the government's latest effort to reach a compromise with
militants of the religious minority.
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi called the appointed governor of
Punjab state, S.S. Ray, and state Police Chief Julius F. Ribiero to
New Delhi on Saturday to plan new initiatives against the violence.
   Ray told reporters that the government would keep up its
``relentless war'' against the Sikh radicals who have been blamed
for more than 630 killings this year.
   The United News of India said Sikh militants shot to death six
people Saturday night in the village of Ragarh in Amritsar
district, adding to the 17 deaths reported since Friday night.
   No new government actions were announced Saturday, but Sikhs in
Punjab expressed fears that Gandhi's goverment would declare an
emergency, severely limiting civil rights and imposing harsh police
rule.
   ``This is an excuse by New Delhi to impose emergency on the
state,'' Darshan Singh Ragi, a Sikh religious leader, said Saturday
at his home near Punjab's capital, Chandigarh. ``The bullet is not
an answer to any problem, either from the militants or New Delhi.''
   At the same time, opposition political leaders and some in
Gandhi's Congress Party demanded action. And three radical groups
issued a statement blaming the latest killings on police agents.
   ``All this is being done to defame the militant Sikh youths in
the eyes of the Sikh masses so that the movement for Khalistan is
weakened,'' said a statement from the radical groups.
   L.K. Advani, leader of the opposition Indian Peoples Party,
demanded in New Delhi that Gandhi impose a security belt along
Punjab's border with Pakistan, believed to be the source of the
AK-47 assault rifles used by the rebels in their latest onslaught.
   Past efforts to seal the porous border, the traditional domain
of smugglers on both sides, have failed.
   Harsh police action, exemplified by the Indian army's raid on
the Sikhs' Golden Temple in Amritsar in 1984, has succeeded only in
turning ordinary Sikhs against the government.
   The June 1984 raid to drive radicals from the shrine left more
than 1,200 people dead, most of them Sikhs. Soon afterwards, Sikh
bodyguards killed Prime Minister Indira Gandhi, who was Gandhi's
mother. Sikh radicals began openly demanding an independent
Khalistan _ ``land of the pure'' in the Punjabi language.
   The killings are spiraling despite the Gandhi government's
direct federal rule over Punjab since last May when it invoked
Indian law to dislodge the elected state government of Sikh
moderates.
   In March alone, 272 victims were gunned down, compared to 215
who died in the first three months of last year.
   The latest police reports confirm the pattern of random killings
with the victims both Hindus and Sikhs.
   In the neighboring villages of Tara and Kaler in Gurdaspur
district, two sets of Hindu brothers, in their 60s and 70s, were
shot to death Friday night by four men with AK-47 rifles.
   In Tara, about 30 miles south of Amritsar, all but two of the 50
houses in the village were deserted by families fleeing the
persistent violence.
   Ram Lal, a Hindu, said he and a few other villagers had been
coming during the day to mind their fields and shops. After Friday
night's slayings, he said: ``We will not come back at all. We are
not able to stay here with the terror.''
   Sikhs, whose religion is a mixture of Hinduism and Islam, make
up only 2 percent of India's 800 million population, but they are a
majority in Punjab.
   The radicals argue that only a separate Sikh nation can save the
minority faith from being overwhelmed by the Hindus, who comprise
more than 80 percent of the country's people.
   Ironically, some Sikh sources say the upsurge in killings
results from a new effort by the government to find a compromise
with the militants through Jasbir Singh Rode, a 34-year-old Sikh
preacher.
   Rode was among about 40 Sikhs who were freed in early March
after being imprisoned without trial. He was promptly elected to
the most powerful post in the Sikh faith amid reports his freedom
was part of a government move to compromise with the radicals _ or
divide them.
   Rode has denied there were any conditions to his release, and
the government has not publicly outlined its plans.
   Gandhi was asked in an interview published Saturday in London's
Financial Times why he had decided to release Rode and other
imprisoned Sikhs.
   ``We have tried everything else,'' he replied.
</TEXT>
