<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reagan-Science     04-02 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Science,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Fears U.S.Decline in Scientific Resarch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan voiced fear
Saturday that the United States could slip to a second-rate world
power in technology, saying scientific research is ``an
indispensable investment in America's future.''
   ``We can travel as far as the eye of our imagination can see,''
Reagan said in his weekly radio address to the nation. ``But one
thing is certain: If we don't, others will, and we'll fall behind.''
   ``This is why I've urged Congress to devote more money to
research,'' Reagan said in the speech delivered from his ranch in
the Santa Ynez Mountains near this seaside resort city.
   ``This year, we'll begin work on the great-grandchild of those
particle accelerators that have meant so much to our economic
growth,'' he said. ``It's called the super-conducting
supercollider. And it will harness the galloping technology of
superconductivity so we can explore sub-atomic particles in ways
we've never been able to before.''
   Reagan also said that ``we'll also continue developing the space
station. When it's in orbit, the space station will let us perform
once-impossible experiments in the weightless environment of outer
space, and understand our world and universe better.''
   ``Meanwhile, back on Earth, we will be pursuing breakthroughs in
biotechnology that promise to revolutionize medicine, agriculture
and protection of the environment,'' he said.
   But in his talk, Reagan acknowledged that scientific research is
expensive.
   ``Some say that we can't afford it _ that we're strapped for
cash,'' he said. ``Well, leadership means making hard choices, even
in an election year.''
   Without citing dollars-and-cents figures, Reagan said that
federal spending for scientific research is 58 percent higher than
a decade ago, after discounting for inflation. But he indicated
this is still not enough.
   ``We've put our research budget under a microscope and looked
for quality and cost-effectiveness,'' he said. ``We've put together
the best program for the taxpayers' dollars.
   ``After all, the American tradition of hope is one we can't
afford to forget.
   ``The problem here is that science, unlike a bridge or an
interstate highway or a courthouse, has no local constituency,'' he
said. ``Federal funding for science is in jeopardy because of
budget constraints. That's why it's my duty as president to draw
its importance to your attention and that of Congress.''
</TEXT>
