<1ST_LINE>r p AM-McGovern     04-02 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-McGovern,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McGovern Warns Against Brokered Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Democratic presidential candidate
George McGovern on Saturday warned Democrats that an attempt to
deny the party's nomination to the front-runner at the convention
could spell defeat in November.
   ``I don't want to see a big, divisive fight at the convention
and a desperate attempt to block the front-runner because I think
that would bring a repeat of 1972,'' McGovern told The Associated
Press.
   McGovern said efforts by some Democrats to block his nomination
despite his delegate lead going into the 1972 Democratic convention
split the party and contributed to his landslide defeat to
then-President Nixon in the general election.
   ``It really cost us heavily. The fallout was devastating,''
McGovern said.
   ``Those last-minute, desperation blocking efforts contributed to
the Democratic defeat in the fall,'' he said. ``We should not
repeat that experience in 1988.''
   McGovern's advice to fall in line behind a front-runner echoes a
similar call by Democratic Party Chairman Paul Kirk, who also wants
the nomination settled before the convention.
   McGovern said a brokered convention is unnecessary because ``the
voters are the brokers and they are making it clear that Michael
Dukakis and Jesse Jackson are the two candidates who command the
most support.''
   ``After the last primary, we should rally around whichever of
these two front-runners has the most delegates,'' he said.
   If Dukakis and Jackson end up in a ``virtual dead heat'' after
all the primaries, then the convention delegates should decide
which will be the candidiate, McGovern said.
   ``But if one of the candidates compiles a significant
first-place win, he is entitled to the nomination,'' McGovern said.
   McGovern said the Democratic race has narrowed to ``a two-man
race now'' between Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson.
   He said neither Sen. Albert Gore of Tennessee nor Sen. Paul
Simon of Illinois is likely to pull ahead, but he said he was not
suggesting they drop out.
   ``That's a judgment they should make, but I think that if at the
end they come up as short as they are now, they should get behind
the front-runner,'' he said.
   McGovern has not endorsed anyone in the race yet. He said
Jackson ``offers a message of hope and reconciliation'' and Dukakis
``offers a record of experience and competence in government.''
   Democrats should evaluate both ``progressive spirited men'' and
nominate the one with the most delegates, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
