<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--France-Ferries     04-02 0133</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--France-Ferries,0137</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Ferry Strikers Vote to Man Ships</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALAIS, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking ferry sailors voted Saturday to
return to work, ending their 17-day walkout in time to carry Easter
holiday travelers across the English Channel.
   Seamen in the French ports of Calais, Dunkirk and Dieppe voted
to accept an agreement worked out Friday between their unions and
the maritime arm of the state-run railroad. The accord provides for
employment guarantees, better working conditions and higher
salaries for part-time employees.
   The workers were readying three idled ferries to serve Easter
Sunday passengers. They join two British ferries that had been
carrying the backed-up traffic alone.
   But on the British side of the Channel, talks broke down Friday
between ferry workers and P and O European Ferries and a two-month
strike continued.
</TEXT>
