<1ST_LINE>r w AM-JudicialNominations     04-02 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Judicial Nominations,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Republicans Complain of Slow Action on Judicial Appointees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Republicans are complaining that the
Democratic-controlled Judiciary Committee hasn't acted quickly
enough on President Reagan's federal judge appointees.
   ``There is no reason, why we can't with a little extra hard
work, hold hearings when necessary and move some of the nominations
presently pending out of this committee,'' Sen. Strom Thurmond,
R-S.C., said at a recent committee hearing.
   But Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., who heads the ad hoc subcommittee
that screens candidates, denied there has been any foot-dragging
over nominations. And Leahy told Thurmond in a letter, ``Your
concern is misplaced.''
   Leahy also said there is no truth to a rumor circulating on
Capitol Hill that the Senate would not take up any executive or
judicial nominations if they were not received by Senate Majority
Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., by April 1.
   ``I don't know where that rumor came from,'' Leahy said in an
interview. ``Sen. Byrd never told me anything like that. Sen.
Kennedy also told me that he has received no such instructions.''
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., who heads the Senate Labor and
Human Resources Committee, has been running the Judiciary Committee
in the absence of Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del., who is at home
recovering from surgery.
   Linda Peek, Byrd's spokeswomen, also said that Byrd had not made
a demand on the Senate's committee chairmen for nominations by
early April.
   Thurmond, backed by other Republicans on the Judiciary panel,
complained about what he called ``the extremely slow pace that the
committee is processing nominations this year.''
   In 1986, he said, the Judiciary Committee received 145
nominations and 139 were confirmed, including two Supreme Court
justices, 11 appeals court judges and 33 district court judges.
That was the last year the Republicans controlled the Senate.
   Thurmond said there are currently 36 judicial nominees waiting
for committee action, five of which are for the appeals court and
21 for the district court.
   Thurmond said some of the nominees have been waiting for nearly
a year for Senate action.
   Others have been waiting months. Specifically, he cited the
nominations of David Treen of Louisiana, which has been pending
eight months, and Stuart Summitt of New York, six months, both for
the appellate court; and Paul Gadola of Michigan, 11 months,
Richard Voorhees of North Carolina, eight months, David Ezra of
Hawaii, four months, Robert Roberto of New York, four months,
Vaughn Walker of California, three months and Howard Levitt of New
York, three months, for the district bench.
   Leahy said Thurmond had written to Biden three times in March
complaining about what he described as ``the extremely slow pace
that the committee is processing nominations so far this year.''
   In a reply, Leahy wrote: ``I believe your concern is misplaced.''
   He said the committee had received nine nominations to the
federal courts this year thus far. He said his committee had
already held hearings on 11 nominations with seven more scheduled.
   ``I can offer you my personal assurance that, as far as I am
concerned, every single judicial nomination that comes before this
committee will be considered fairly, thoroughly, and without any
unjustified delay,'' Leahy wrote. ``I know Joe (Biden) shares this
attitude, and I believe the committee has lived up to this standard
throughout his chairmanship.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
