<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 1339EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BetterLearning     04-02 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Better Learning,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seminar Examines Ways To Improve College</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study that is looking at ways to help
students enjoy college has found that the happiest students at
Harvard University are athletes.
   The preliminary study also has found that too many students
don't give enough thought to their major and suggests a need for
better advising.
   The results are too new to have been properly interpreted,
cautions Richard F. Light, director of the Harvard Seminar on
Assessment. He suspects athletes are happier because of the social
life inherent in their activity.
   ``Almost by definition anybody in an athletic group has a group
of people they become very good friends with,'' Light said in a
recent interview.
   The seminar is a three-year, $350,000 project funded by private,
federal and college funds. It involves 90 faculty, administrators
and students from Northeastern colleges including Amherst,
Brandeis, Pennsylvania, Princeton, Smith, Williams, MIT and Brown.
   Among the findings halfway through the project, a student at
Wellesley College said she chose a joint major in Middle East and
peace studies after a friend suggested it fit her personality, said
Wellesley professor David Pillemar.
   Another student chose psychobiology the first week of her
freshman year because her mother, leafing through a course
catalogue, thought it sounded interesting.
   ``A lot of people feel an improvement in the overall college
experience may not come from teaching the subject a tiny bit better
but from better advising,'' Light said.
   The researchers also have found that less than half the female
freshmen who entered a science program at Dartmouth, Harvard or
Yale graduated in the field, but they aren't sure yet what that
means, Light said.
   ``One interpretation is that is bad _ we're losing talented
women,'' he said. ``The other is that's great, they're making
choices.''
   The researchers will examine 18 separate areas, including the
effects of part-time work and extra-curricular activities on
student success.
   And at a time when Secretary of Education William J. Bennett has
accused colleges of ``ripping off'' students through poor
instruction, the project will look at different methods of
instruction, ways to improve student writing and student advisory
programs.
   Researchers expect to issue a report this summer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
