<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Meese 1stLd-Writethru a0542 04-02 1044</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0542,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Probe Running Into Roadblocks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, The latest, to add detail; INSERTS two
grafs after 5th pvs to add explanation why testimony can't be
compelled; picks up 6th graf pvs, On Friday</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Independent counsel James McKay's criminal
investigation of Attorney General Edwin Meese III has run into
roadblocks because key witnesses have refused to cooperate with the
probe.
   Among those who have erected a wall of silence that McKay has
been unable to penetrate is a central figure in the probe, longtime
Meese friend E. Robert Wallach.
   The attorney general's former financial manager, W. Franklyn
Chinn _ who was introduced to Meese by Wallach _ also isn't talking
to McKay. Chinn and Wallach were indicted in December in the
Wedtech scandal, one of the areas in which Meese has been under
investigation since last May 11.
   Former Wedtech consultant R. Kent London, another indicted in
the Wedtech scandal, also has also refused to talk to McKay.
   The latest figure to stand in the way of McKay's probe is Swiss
oil man Bruce Rappaport. Sources familiar with the probe said he
decided at the last minute not to give a deposition in London,
where he had agreed to meet with McKay's investigators, on
questions of whether Meese may have been part of a bribe conspiracy
in connection with a $1 billion Iraqi pipeline project. The
Washington Post reported that Rappaport changed his mind because he
was afraid he might not remember everything accurately.
   Federal prosecutors decided to have criminal charges filed
against Wallach, Chinn and London and decided not to grant them
immunity from prosecution to compel their testimony.
   In December, after the three invoked their Fifth Amendment right
against self incrimination, McKay said he might seek their
testimony again after their criminal trial on racketeering charges
in the Wedtech scandal.
   On Friday, McKay said there was insufficient evidence to date to
warrant indicting Meese in connection with a $1 billion Iraqi
pipeline plan in which Wallach was involved, or a possible conflict
of interest involving Meese's telephone company stock, a matter in
which Chinn was involved.
   Meese said he was ``gratified by the action and the statement.''
   At a news conference, Meese referred to the independent
counsel's investigation as ``an exhaustive process. ... When that
particular process is completed I think there will be no doubt in
anybody's mind what the facts are and at that time I will rest on
that judgment.''
   When a reporter pointed out that principals in the investigation
weren't talking, Meese responded, ``I'm not going to comment on any
aspect or details of the inquiry. That's something that will have
to be determined by the independent counsel.''
   Sources familiar with McKay's probe have said that although the
special prosecutor has not found sufficient evidence to indict
Meese, he could issue a sharply critical report about Meese's
conduct.
   The grand jury will continue to examine the pipeline and
telephone stock matters mostly to tie up ``loose ends,'' the source
said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   If McKay dismisses the grand jury without bringing charges, he
could retain his appointment or seek reappointment if new evidence
surfaces later, the source said.
   The grand jury is expected to question Meese, his wife, Ursula,
and U.S. Circuit Judge Douglas H. Ginsburg, who was head of the
Justice Department's antitrust division during the breakup of the
American Telephone & Telegraph Co.
   In regard to the pipeline, Wallach, who was Rappaport's lawyer,
obtained Meese's help in arranging a meeting with then-National
Security Adviser Robert McFarlane to help boost the pipeline
project.
   Four months later, Wallach wrote Meese a memo that Wallach said
was based on conversations with Rappaport. It said a portion of up
to $700 million from the oil pipeline would be funneled to the
Labor Party of then-Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres.
   That raised questions of whether Meese, who has said he doesn't
recall reading that portion of the memo, may have violated the
Foreign Corrupt Practices Act barring bribes to foreign officials.
   Without being able to question Wallach or Rappaport, McKay is at
a dead end.
   Another part of McKay's probe the independent counsel says he
has insufficient evidence on which to seek indictment is Meese's
ownership of $14,000 in stock in the regional Bell telephone
companies.
   Chinn was involved in the Baby Bell stck ownership at a critical
juncture.
   Meese as attorney general met with executives of four of the
regional Bell telephone companies at a time when he owned the stock.
   At the time, the Bell companies were seeking to reverse the
Justice Department's position opposing the Bells' expansion into
new areas of business. Meese ended up approving a reversal of the
department's position early in 1987.
   Meese says he had intended to sell the stock in 1985 but
couldn't because he had lost the stock certificates.
   Complicating McKay's investigation was the fact that Meese had
signed a transfer of property agreement with Chinn assigning the
Baby Bell stock to the financial manager for more than two years.
Meese initially listed the stock as having been sold on his
financial disclosure forms for 1985 and 1986.
   Meese got replacement certificates late last summer and finally
sold the stock himself after getting Chinn to return it to him.
   Meese says he considered the transfer agreement a legitimate
divestiture of the stock. But McKay's investigators are unable to
delve into details of the arrangement because they were unable to
question Chinn.
   In December, McKay said he had insufficient evidence at that
time to seek an indictment of Meese in the Wedtech scandal and said
he might seek testimony from Wallach and Chinn again after their
trial.
   In the Wedtech probe, then-White House counselor Meese
interceded on the company's behalf at Wallach's behest to assist
the firm in its efforts to obtain a $32 million no-bid contract to
build small engines for the Army.
   The company got the contract following a crucial White House
meeting called by Meese's deputy. Three years later, Meese set up a
financial partnership after Wallach introduced Meese to Chinn _ who
at the time was doing work for Wedtech and who later sat on the
company's board of directors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
