<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Trade-Democrats     04-02 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade-Democrats,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Trade Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Byrd Wants Heat On Reagan to Sign Trade Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd asked
Americans on Saturday to pressure President Reagan into signing
comprehensive trade legislation.
   ``Write the president and tell him ... that this trade bill will
help you and help America feel proud again,'' Byrd, D-W.Va., urged
in the Democratic Party's weekly radio address.
   Under a compromise worked out by House and Senate negotiators
Thursday night, the U.S. trade representative would have the
authority to impose import curbs on the goods of nations who
violate trade agreements. The president could waive the curbs if he
thought their cost would outweigh the benefit.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater on Friday renewed the
threat of a veto by President Reagan, saying the bill unreasonably
ties the president's hands and that the administration has ``grave
reservations'' about it.
   Byrd complained that ``the president has done nothing but cry
protectionism and wave his veto pen'' as the ability of the United
States to compete has eroded.
   ``This is not the time for a veto,'' he said. ``The trade bill
is a strong comprehensive bill that helps American workers help
themselves.''
   He said the Democrats' ``goal has been a bill that the president
will sign,'' adding, ``We have extended our hand in cooperation.''
   ``The president may not understand what this bill means to the
American worker ... I think you do,'' Byrd said in urging his
listeners to write to the White House.
   The measure also would impose import restrictions to punish
Toshiba Corp. of Japan for a subsidiary's role in selling
computerized submarine propeller milling equipment to the Soviet
Union.
   And, it would require employers to give workers a 60-day notice
of plant closings and large layoffs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880402-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 1355EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Democrats-RadioText     04-02 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Radio Text,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Trade-Democrats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the Democratic Party's
weekly radio address, delivered Saturday by Senate Majority Leader
Robert C. Byrd of West Virginia:
   Good afternoon. This is Sen. Robert C. Byrd from West Virginia.
The Congress is putting the finishing touches on a very important
trade bill.
   It is not a minute too soon. Our nation's trade policy is in
shambles. You know it. I know it. We import more than we export. We
send more of our money overseas than we get back. We are losing
American jobs. We are losing our industrial base. We are in hock to
foreign lenders.
   Once it wasn't so. America traded hard all over the world. The
result was money in the bank and jobs for American workers. America
ran a trade surplus. ``Made in the USA'' was on the product that
everybody looked for. Americans took pride in being No. 1.
   Now our ability to compete is eroding. For seven years the
president has refused to act. ``Free trade,'' he says. What about
fair trade? The president has done nothing but cry protectionism
and wave his veto pen. Yet, unless we change the way America trades
the tide of change will sweep our economic destiny out of our hands.
   You know what I am talking about. You see it in the frustration
of all the young families who cannot afford to buy their first
home. You understand it when American companies take their jobs
overseas.
   America is rapidly developing a treadmill economy; everyone is
working harder just to keep up; yet we still seem to be losing
ground to our foreign competition. Our prosperity has always been
built on working smarter as well as harder. Yet, despite our new
technology and effort to compete, we have been losing the
productivity race.
   For years the Reagan administration has left trade policy to the
whims of the international marketplace and our foreign competition.
The administration has refused to act. It has had a do-nothing
trade policy.
   It is time to get America moving again. The stakes are high and
measured in jobs, and in the life style we pass on to our children,
and in our vital national security.
   Congress will soon send the president a comprehensive trade
bill. We are not ready to say good-bye to the America of our
dreams. What must be done to rebuild America's dreams?
   First, America must boost its exports. Selling more goods
overseas lowers the deficit. It is that simple. Our bill gives the
president new tools to open new markets for American products.
   Second, we must take steps to promote America's long run
competitive strengths. We want to see more investment in
individuals and in ideas. That means a better educated work force,
stronger laws to protect American inventions from piracy by foreign
firms.
   Third, we want to give American industry and workers the
opportunity to retool and retrain quickly. I have seen the
devastating impact in my own state of West Virginia where closed
factories leave workers and whole communities struggling for their
economic future.
   This trade bill sharply improves the opportunities for workers
to retrain, to start new careers. If American workers want to move
to expanding parts of the job market they ought to have that chance.
   Finally, this trade bill would prevent foreign investors from
dominating industries vital to our national security. America
cannot control its destiny if our foreign competition is buying up
our assets.
   Opening new markets for exports, giving American industry a leg
up to retool, creating new opportunities for American workers to
retrain, keeping America's destiny in American hands, educating our
children for a prosperous future _ these are the essentials of this
trade bill, which the president would veto.
   In the last few months you have heard a lot of talk about this
trade bill from the president. I am sure you will hear more. Our
goal has been a bill that the president will sign. We have extended
our hand in cooperation.
   This is not a time for a veto. The trade bill is a strong
comprehensive bill that helps American industry and helps American
workers help themselves.
   The president may not understand what this bill means to the
American worker, to young families who cannot buy their first home,
to the unemployed worker who has lost his job to a foreign
competitor. I think you do.
   So write the president. Tell him of your concerns. Let him know
that this trade bill will help America feel proud again. Let's put
America's future back in American hands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
