<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Pilot     04-02 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Pilot,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqi Pilot Says He Is Shocked By Chemical Weapon Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iraqi pilot held captive by Iran said
Saturday he was shocked to learn how many civilians were killed in
an Iraqi gas attack on a border town and assumed the raid was a
mistake.
   Air Force Maj. Ahmed Sakr Salaleh, 31, said he was shown an
Iranian documentary of the aftermath of the raid two weeks ago on
the Kurdish town of Halabja, in northeastern Iraq.
   ``All of us suffer seeing these pictures,'' Salaleh told
reporters in Tehran. ``I ask God to take all of them to paradise.''
   Salaleh said he was aware that the Iraqi air force had been
dropping chemical weapons but added: ``We are under orders. We are
officers.''
   He said the chemical bombs were dropped to halt Iranian advances
into Iraqi territory. Iran and Iraq have been at war since
September 1980.
   Iraq has denied using chemical weapons, which are banned by
international law.
   Iran has said it captured large tracts of territory in northeast
Iraq in league with Kurdish separatists. Iraq said Saturday it
routed the attackers.
   Iran says chemical weapons raids on Halabja, 160 miles northeast
of Baghdad, killed 5,000 people and wounded another 5,000 on March
16-17.
   The Iraqi pilot said his Soviet-built Sukhoi Su-22 was shot down
30 miles south of Halabja on March 18 after the gas attacks were
over.
   He said he earlier had released four conventional-explosive
1,100-pound bombs over uninhabited territory when clouds prevented
bombing of a road.
   Salaleh said he ejected and parachuted into Iranian-held
territory. Iran has claimed shooting down more than a dozen Iraqi
warplanes since mid-March.
   The Iraqi officer said he was not involved in the Halabja
attack. He said he was assigned to drop a chemical bomb into
wetland border territory of Iraq in 1983 to prevent an Iranian
offensive there.
   The bomb he dropped then was put on his plane by a crew in
civilian clothes who arrived at the air force base with a truck and
trailer with civilian plates, Salaleh said.
   He estimated about 50 planes raided Halabja from March 16-18
after the Iranians and Kurdish guerrillas captured the town.
Salaleh, speaking in relatively good English, said he thought the
chemical-bomb attack was a ``mistake.''
   He said one possible explanation was that Iraqi intelligence did
not know the inhabitants were still in the town.
   Salaleh said he had been well treated since he was captured but
had not yet been transferred to a prisoner-of-war camp.
   He said he had heard on Iraqi television that Iran has used
artillery gas shells but had no confirmation of this, adding that
Iraqi forces had been issued gas masks.
   Iran has denied using the internationally banned chemical
weapons, but has said it has the capability to produce them.
   Iraq has repeatedly denied using the weapons, while coupling its
denials with assurances it will use ``all means'' at its disposal
to defend its territory.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880402-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 1418EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FederatedSale Bjt   04-02 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Federated Sale, Bjt,0738</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sale of Department Store Giant Will Bring Changes to Retail
Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sale of Federated Department Stores Inc. to
Campeau Corp. is more than just a retailer changing hands. Analysts
fear the $6.58 billion deal may lead to more centralization and
less innovation in the retail industry .
   When ownership of the nation's fifth-largest retailer passes to
Campeau, the Toronto-based developer will do what it did when it
acquired Allied Stores Corp. at the end of 1986: pare the company
down, sell its less attractive divisions and keep its most
profitable stores.
   The forecasts are that Federated, now a collection of diverse
department and specialty stores, will become a centralized retailer
with few differences among its various units.
   ``The structure will be much more of a chain store company,''
said Walter Loeb, a retail industry analyst with the investment
firm Morgan Stanley & Co.
   Robert H. Morosky, the president of Allied Stores, denied
Saturday that Campeau would centralize buying operations of
Federated department store divisions that include Bloomingdale's
and Abraham & Straus in New York, Lazarus in the Midwest and
Burdine's in Florida.
   Operations such as distribution will be centralized, he said,
but the stores' merchandise mix ``will be determined by the local
department store divisions.''
   However, Loeb predicted that under Campeau, Federated would
consolidate operations such as purchasing and marketing that are
now carried out separately by the Federated units.
   ``The merchandise will be uniform,'' said Loeb, who has been
tracking the industry for almost 40 years. ``It's bad for the whole
industry.''
   Retail industry watchers want to see what Loeb called
``innovativeness and testing,'' which helps develop new styles and
trends. When there are more retailers buying and experimenting,
there is a greater opportunity for growth in the retail industry.
   Friday's announcement of an agreement between Federated and
Campeau ended a grueling takeover battle that began Jan. 25.
Federated resisted Campeau's overtures for a month, agreed to
negotiate with the Canadian company, and then in early March
accepted a buyout offer from R.H. Macy & Co. Inc.
   The wrangling continued for yet another month, until Macy agreed
on Friday to bow out. But the New York-based retailer came away
from the fight with the Federated divisions it wanted most,
Bullock's stores in California and the Southwest and the San
Francisco-based I. Magnin chain.
   Many retail industry analysts were rooting for Macy to win the
battle outright. They believed Macy would have re-energized
Federated's department store divisions in much the way Macy has
revitalized its own image in recent years.
   Campeau, they believed, was interested more in Federated's real
estate than its retail operations. The stores would give Campeau
Chairman Robert Campeau an instant entree into major shopping malls
in the United States.
   The expected sale of several of Federated's divisions represents
a chance for the retailing industry to move in a new direction, but
whether that happens depends on who buys the stores.
   Morosky said Campeau will retain Bloomingdale's, Abraham &
Straus, Lazarus and Burdine's, as well as Tennessee-based
Goldsmith's and Atlanta-based Rich's department stores.
   Campeau has already agreed to sell Federated's Texas-based
Foley's and Boston-based Filene's department stores to May
Department Stores Co.
   Federated's discount and specialty store chains and its
supermarkets divisions are expected to go on the block. However,
Morosky said, ``After we comple te our review, we might choose to
keep certain divisions.''
   Campeau wants to sell some of the divisions to pay off debt
incurred in the Federated purchase and to simplify operations,
Morosky said.
   Thomas Tashjian, an analyst with the Los Angeles investment firm
Seidler Amdec Securities Inc., said recently that if Campeau sells
Federated's units to larger companies _ such as May _ it would
continue the trend toward central control and ``sameness.''
   However, he said, if the stores are sold to smaller companies or
to entrepreneurial management groups, it would mean increased
competition, which in turn leads to growth in the retail industry.
   ``The long-term benefit is to the consumer,'' Tashjian said.
   Morosky said Campeau already has received inquiries from
retailers, existing management and real estate developers about
some of the Federated stores. He said the stores would go on sale
several days after the purchase of Federated is completed.
</TEXT>
