<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Biotech 1stLd-Writethrough a0544 04-02 0767</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Biotech, 1st Ld-Writethrough, a0544,710</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 2 grafs new to update with Reagan comment; pickup 2nd
graf pvs ``For hundreds</NOTE>
<HEAD>Patent Backlog Stymies Biotech Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's biotechnology industry, hailed
Saturday by President Reagan for its ``promise to revolutionize
medicine, agriculture and protection of the environment,'' is
seriously hampered by government delays on patent applications,
congressional and industry officials say.
   Reagan, in a radio address from his California ranch, called for
renewed U.S. determination to remain the world's scientific leader,
noting that ``over the years, we've secured far more patents than
any other country.'' He cited biotechnology as one of the most
fertile fields for exploration.
   For hundreds of small biotech companies developing new drugs,
plants and other products through molecular biology, the issuance
of a patent can mean instant success. But the wait can take more
than four years, leaving some firms to ponder the risk of marketing
their products without patent protection.
   In some of the biotech examining units at the U.S. Office of
Patents and Trademarks, ``it takes an average of 27 months just to
open an application file, and another 25 months to award or deny a
patent,'' complained Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore, whose House Small
Business subcommittee is looking into the problem.
   Biotech products have begun to pour out of the laboratories of
the 12-year-old industry, doubling the backlog of patent
applications from 3,903 in 1985 to 7,821 by August of last year. By
some estimates, 11,000 applications are now pending.
   According to industry forecasts, biotech sales in U.S. markets
will total $650 million this year. Barring further bureaucratic
snags, the industry projects domestic sales of $3.4 billion by 1993
and $13.2 billion by 1998. International sales could triple the
domestic figure, officials say.
   But ``the longer it takes of patents to be issued, the longer we
work in a black hole,'' says Hubert J.P. Schoemaker, chairman of
Centocor, Inc.
   That complaint is echoed by officials of Genentech, which has
begun marketing a much-acclaimed drug known as TPA _ a clot buster
for heart attack victims. Genentech's patent application is still
pending, however, and several other companies are planning to
market their own TPA drugs.
   Turnover among biotech patent examiners, lured to private
companies by higher pay, has been part of the problem. Wyden said
the turnover was 50 percent last year, though the patent office has
created 10 new biotech positions for a total of 42, and recently
consolidated all those positions within a special biotech unit.
   Patent Commissioner Donald J. Quigg said, meanwhile, that the
office is seeking approval from the Office of Personnel Management
to create special pay rates for the examiners, who usually have a
doctorate or master's degree in molecular biology or biochemistry.
   Quigg said the goal of the patent office is to process all
applications within 18 months, but that target likely won't be met
until 1993 or 1994.
   To encourage inventions, the Constitution gives inventors the
right to a short-term exclusive monopoly on products that result
from their new ideas. Currently, the monopoly lasts 17 years.
   To make sure the invention is indeed new, and not an obvious
twist to existing technology, the patent office examines
applications in light of previous patents.
   Lack of patents leads firms to hold their products off the
market, or to risk theft of their invention if they sell without
full protection. Since the United States does not publish
applications after 18 months, as all other major countries do, the
backlog may lead several companies to undertake duplicate research
they would not perform if they knew someone else was likely to win
a patent.
   ``Increasing backlogs in the processing of patent applications
will have serious deleterious effects on continuing investment and
the maintenance of the United States' leadership position,'' said
George B. Rathmann, president of Amgen Inc. of Thousand Oaks,
Calif., in testimony to Wyden's subcommittee.
   Linda I. Miller, a vice president of PaineWebber Inc., a Wall
Street investment firm, found in a survey of four dozen
prospectuses by biotechnology companies that nearly all mentioned
uncertainty about patent protection as a potential risk for
investors.
   She gave the subcommittee charts of price movements of several
stocks, up when specific patents were awarded and down when patent
disputes broke out between two companies.
   The applications backlog appears to be growing at 20 percent a
year, she reported.
   ``With the lack of clarity of property rights in biotechnology
in the United States, many companies are developing similar
products _ expending valuable resources, both human and financial _
on me-too programs,'' she said.
</TEXT>
