<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Archaeology-Stabbings     04-02 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Archaeology-Stabbings,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Dead, Two Wounded In Archaeological Company Rampage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST CONSHOHOCKEN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who allegedly stabbed two
co-workers to death at an archaeological firm and severely wounded
two others was a former prison inmate who was apparently hired out
of sympathy, police and friends of the victims said.
   All four victims were ``stabbed with a knife or other sharp
instrument,'' police Capt. John Sheehan said. He would not say if a
weapon had been recovered.
   The Philadelphia Daily News reported Saturday that the stabbings
occurred after the attacker tried to rape one of the women who was
killed, but Lower Merion Township detectives refused to confirm
that.
   Friday's attack occurred in a house where the archaeological
firm, SJS Industries, examined artifacts. Its excavation was
federally mandated as part of a sewer line installation in this
Philadelphia suburb, said Bill Stanyard, 32, who has worked with
SJS.
   Lower Merion Township Police Lt. John Maloney identified the
dead women as Clarice J. Dorner, 30, of Elk Grove Village, Ill.,
and Annaliese H. Killoran, 22, of Lynn, Mass. They were graduate
students in anthropology and archaeology.
   Glenn W. Sheehan, 39, of Conshohocken, and his pregnant wife,
Anne M. Jensen, 31, were taken to hospitals. They were working on
their doctorates in anthropology at Bryn Mawr College in nearby
Bryn Mawr, said college spokeswoman Catherine LaFarge.
   Police flooded the wooded area, but failed to find the attacker.
Police also closed the Schuylkill Expressway, the state's most
congested, for an hour, leading to an accident involving a truck on
a side road.
   Police were looking for Arthur Faulkner, a Philadelphia man
described as 40 to 45. WCAU-TV, quoting police sources, reported
that Faulkner was released from prison last October after serving
time for attempted rape.
   Sheehan's friends said he often hired former convicts whom he
felt needed a second chance.
   John Jensen, Anne Jensen's brother, said he had worked with
Faulkner and others at the site. He described Faulkner as a former
inmate who seemed interested in his job as a digger.
   ``I just couldn't believe it,'' he said. ``I talked to him
yesterday. He was a solid worker, he never complained.''
   ``Glenn (Sheehan) is on the Philadelphia prison board and he got
him (Faulkner) from there or the Salvation Army,'' Jensen said.
``He had been assured that he had no violent past.''
   Sheehan is a member of the board of the Philadelphia Prison
Society, a prison advocacy group. Telephone calls placed Saturday
to the society and the Salvation Army went unanswered.
   Sheehan was taken to Bryn Mawr Hospital with stab wounds of the
legs, arms and abdomen. Hospital spokeswoman Elaine McVay said he
was in stable condition Saturday.
   His wife was in serious but stable condition Saturday at
Hahnemann Hospital in Philadelphia, spokeswoman Phyllis Fisher
said. She suffered multiple stab wounds to the back and had
internal injuries, but her fetus apparently suffered no trauma, a
spokeswoman said.
</TEXT>
