<1ST_LINE>u i AM-India-SriLanka 1stLd-Writethru   04-02 0850</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0506,0873</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Troops Seek Elusive Sri Lankan Rebels</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with three grafs to CORRECT spelling of sarong. Pick up
4th pvs, `Every few...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATTICALOA, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight months after they landed to
enforce a peace accord between rival ethnic groups, Indian soldiers
are chasing a faceless enemy.
   The Tamil rebels, who have waged a four-year war of guerrilla
fighting and terrorism against Sri Lanka's Sinhalese majority, seem
to be everywhere and nowhere at once.
   Every young man is a potential foe, whether dressed in trousers
or the plaid sarongs favored in the steamy heat of this tropical
island 18 miles off India's southern coast.
   Every few miles along potholed roads, Indian soldiers man
sandbagged checkpoints where they halt travelers who come on foot,
on bicycles and jammed into minibuses.
   Despite an Indian force estimated at 50,000 by the Indians and
as high as 100,000 by Sri Lankan officials, a ragtag band of Tamil
Tiger rebels continues to kill and maim Indian soldiers, massacre
Sinhalese villagers and extort money from Tamils, Sinhalese and
Moslems alike.
   The Indians say there are about 2,500 hard-core fighters in the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the largest rebel group. The
Tigers claim there are only 175.
   More than 8,000 Sri Lankans, mostly Sinhalese, have been killed
since 1984. India has lost at least 400 soldiers since Oct. 10,
1987, when it launched an offensive to disarm the Tigers.
   The Indians sent troops to control the rebels as part of a peace
plan they sponsored in July 1987. The agreement granted some
autonomy to Tamils, but it was rejected by extremists on both sides
of the conflict.
   India, Sri Lanka's northern neighbor, has a large Tamil minority
of its own.
   Despite India's firepower, armor, lumbering troop trucks,
darting Jeep patrols and helicopters _ and allied government forces
_ the Tigers slip from village to village and even into big towns
like Batticaloa.
   In Arapattai, 5 miles south of Batticaloa on Sri Lanka's eastern
coast, Indian soldiers recently checked pedestrians' identity cards
and munched snacks purchased in local shops.
   A five-minute walk away, a man sought by the Indians for
harboring Tiger fighters said the rebels could not be vanquished.
``Our fight is reasonable. We must win,'' he said, switching on an
electric fan as an elderly relative tended his infant twins.
   The man asked not to be identified, although the Indians know
his name and where he lives. They also know that the minute they
come after him, his neighbors will sound an alarm and he will slip
away _ as he has done several times before _ through the fences of
woven palm fronds that make Arapattai look like an impenetrable
maze.
   The Tigers are fighting for an autonomous region in northern and
eastern Sri Lanka. Although Tamils make up only 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people, they are a majority in Northern and
Eastern provinces.
   In Eastern Province's Batticaloa District, the population of
about 365,000 is 72 percent Tamil. Sinhalese account for only 3
percent there, while Moslems comprise 25 percent.
   The Tamils say they have been discriminated against in
education, jobs and by a 1956 law that made Sinhalese the official
language of Sri Lanka. Tamils are mainly Hindu, and the Sinhalese
are Buddhists.
   Batticaloa, population 46,000, is a town of poor fishermen,
small shops and many churches, monuments to the missionary efforts
of the Dutch, Portuguese and British colonial eras.
   The Indian presence keeps armed Tigers out of clear sight. But,
according to residents who feared for their safety if their names
were published, the Tigers make themselves felt in other ways.
   ``They send notes asking for money. People who refuse are
killed,'' a middle-aged Tamil said. ``They have people in the
banks, so they know how much money we have.''
   But that Tamil, like others who described the Tigers'
fund-raising tactics, defended the rebels' cause as a just fight
for Tamil rights.
   ``Just because they're militant, they're not unreasonable,''
said one Tamil bureaucrat.
   A occasional land mine or hand grenade explodes in Batticaloa
near a group of the Indian soldiers or the predominantly Sinhalese
Sri Lankan police force.
   Sometimes, the Indian response is disciplined. Other times, it
verges on panic, Batticaloa residents said.
   On March 26, a grenade was thrown at the Sri Lankan police
headquarters. No one was hurt by the grenade, but it prompted three
hours of gunfire that injured a half-dozen people, including two
schoolchildren.
   Sri Lankan police officers declined to say whether their men
fired, but Batticaloa residents said the police apparently started
the shooting and the Indians followed with automatic rifle fire.
   ``The roads were packed with children,'' said the Rev. Harry
Miller, a Jesuit from New Orleans who has spent the past 40 years
at St. Michael's school. ``The schoolchildren just panicked. They
dropped their books and bicycles and ran.''
   An Indian major, speaking on condition of anonymity, admitted
that mistakes have been made. ``There is no doubt there is some
confusion,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
