<DOCNO> AP880402-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 1447EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Soviet-Minorities     04-02 0613</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Minorities,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Armenian Leader May Have Instigated Disturbances</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The disturbances in Soviet Armenia may have
been instigated by a local leader who was a target of Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's anti-corruption campaign, according to analysts.
   The local leader may have capitalized on unrest exacerbated by
Gorbachev's drive for economic reform, known as ``perestroika,''
and his allowance of greater public debate of some topics, known as
``glasnost,'' according to a government analyst.
   Similar disturbances have been reported in each of the 15
republics in the Soviet Union. And in many instances, the
demonstrations grew out of Russian resentment of Kremlin efforts to
help non-Russians by giving them jobs and raising their living
standards, scholar Paul Goble of Washington said in an article last
year.
   ``Many Russians came to the conclusion that what had appeared to
be reasonable affirmative action for the non-Russians was in fact
unreasonable reverse discrimination against themselves,'' Goble
wrote.
   That system worked under the late Soviet leader Leonid Brezhnev,
who tolerated corruption and widespread inefficiency in the
economy. Under his leadership, a Russian and a non-Russian were
frequently allowed to hold redundant jobs.
   But Gorbachev, in his effort to streamline the economy, has
stepped on a lot of ethnic toes.
   ``It is not that he is coming down hard on any ethnic group. It
is that he is trying to make the economy more efficient,'' said
Nancy Lubin, a Georgetown University professor.
   Ostensibly, the demonstrations in Armenia, a largely Christian
republic, stemmed from Armenian desire to administer the largely
Armenian region of Nagorno-Karabakh, which is in neighboring
Azerbaijan, a predominately Moslem republic.
   But the unrest began after party newspapers criticized the
Armenian party leader, Karen Demirchyan, said an administration
source, who like other government analysts interviewed, spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Demirchyan, 55, named to his post in 1974, was attacked last
June by Gorbachev, who said that reforms were ``stuck in a rut'' in
Armenia, and that Demirchyan and his underlings showed ``totally
unjustified complacency'' toward corruption.
   Reformers in the Armenia Communist Party attempted to oust
Demirchyan during a meeting of the party Central Committee last
December, but were thwarted, according to Elizabeth Fuller, a
Soviet-watcher based in Munich.
   The authoritative Communist Party daily Pravda hinted strongly
of a purge in Armenia.
   ``The absolute majority of Armenian working people are honest
persons who conscientiously attend their duty, and it is not their
fault that the process of democratization and renewal is meeting
with fierce resistance of perestroika,'' Pravda said in December.
``People yearn for genuine changes.''
   The demonstrations in Armenia began two months later ``with
either the complicity or encouragement of Demirchyan,'' said a
government analyst. ``We believe he backed them, or encouraged
them, to warn Moscow that getting rid of him could cause trouble.''
   Demirchyan has survived the upheaval, although some party
leaders in Azerbaijan and Nagorno-Karabakh have been removed.
   Gorbachev's efficiency drive has cost local jobs in Kazakhstan,
the scene of riots in December 1986. Gorbachev abolished the
Kazakhstan Ministry of Non-Ferrous Metallurgy, transferring its
functions to a parallel ministry in Moscow, but ``throwing a lot of
educated Kazakhs out of work,'' said a government analyst.
   Similarly, Gorbachev's highly celebrated campaign against
alcohol has cost jobs in the vineyards of Armenia, creating tension
there, said the analyst.
   The ethnic unrest has prompted Gorbachev to announce that he
will convene the policy-making Communist Party Central Committee to
discuss the issue at an as yet unannounced date.
   Gorbachev probably will continue to crack down, as he did in
Armenia and neighboring Azerbaijan, ``to show people that they
can't get what they want by going to the streets,'' an analyst said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
