<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 1508EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-OhioSpill     04-02 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ohio Spill,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diesel Oil Spill Stretches More Than 50 Miles On Ohio River</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS S. WATSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A diesel oil spill floated along about 50
miles of the Ohio River on Saturday, and the Coast Guard and state
officials were searching for the source of the fuel.
   ``We want to make sure it's not still flowing into the river,''
said Lt. Eric Mosher. ``We're looking for the source and have teams
from Louisville and Cincinnati making bank searches.''
   The oil extended from the area of Madison in southeastern
Indiana to Louisville.
   Indiana conservation authorities also helped in the search,
Mosher added. Barge fleets, towboats and holding tanks along the
river were all being checked.
   Mosher said the water was too choppy for an attempt to contain
the oil slick.
   The spill apparently caused no serious problem for communities
that use the river as a source of drinking water and Mosher said
none of them had closed water intake valves.
   ``We're treating (the river water) for some of the byproducts of
oil, but the river is relatively warm and it doesn't look like it's
emulsifying and it looks like it will float past,'' said Jerry
Ford, manager of administrative services for the Louisville Water
Co.
   ``Shutting down (intake valves) is always an alternative to
treating, but when you have oil byproducts that will float on top
of the water, normally you don't have that much effect,'' Ford
said. He noted that the intake valves are on the river bottom.
   Indiana State Police Sgt. James Hickerson said the slick was not
thick and heavy all the way, but there were traces for the entire
distance.
   Patrolman Tim Armstrong, in Madison, Ind., said his department
began getting reports of a strong diesel smell from the river about
7:30 p.m. Friday, and the spill was discovered after sunup Saturday
morning.
   Officials were unable to say what effect the spill might have on
the environment.
   ``It depends on (the oil's) consistency as to whether or not it
will threaten wildlife,'' Ford said.
   ``We've had no fish kill and haven't observed loss of any marine
life,'' said Sgt. Carroll Henneke of the Indiana Department of
Natural Resources. ``We don't anticipate any simply because this
appears to be floating. If it doesn't settle in, we don't expect to
lose any of our fishery.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
