<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Chicken-Liberation     04-02 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chicken-Liberation,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Animal Rights Group Raids Large Hatchery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GILROY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Animal Liberation Front claimed
responsibility Saturday for a raid on a large hatchery in what it
called an ``Easter liberation for life'' for at least 28 hens.
   Members of the underground group broke into the Davis Poultry
Co. & Egg Ranch in rural Gilroy late Friday, stole 28 hens and
spraypainted the walls and grounds, said Santa Clara County Deputy
Sheriff Roland Perez.
   The underground group said it raided the farm because of alleged
``atrocious conditions'' such as overcrowding and disease,
according to Margo Tannenbaum, president of Action for Animals in
San Bernardino.
   Tannenbaum said she was asked by the Animal Liberation Front to
speak for them. The group claimed it took more than 78 laying hens,
but did not say what it did with them.
   The raid was the second by the group this Easter season. It also
took responsibility for a March 27 raid on a rabbit-breeding
company in Hayward, where 73 rabbits were taken in protest over the
slaughter of rabbits for medical research, furs and meat.
   Perez said a book on animal liberation was left behind and that
the sheriff's department would increase patrols of the area. He
said the three owners of the poultry farm were meeting with
investigators.
   The owners could not immediately be reached for comment by
telephone. A clerk at the farm said she knew nothing about the raid.
   In its statement, the Animal Liberation Front said: ``A hatchery
perpetuates the most abominable animal exploitation and abuse. We
want everyone to think about how these hens live in order to
furnish the eggs that are decorated in the celebration of `eternal
life.'''
   The group called its two raids an ``Easter liberation for life.''
   Tannenbaum, who was also used as a media conduit after the
rabbit-breeding company raid, told The Associated Press in a
telephone interview that six members of the underground group
participated in the hatchery raid.
</TEXT>
