<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia-Tomasek,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tomasek Says Government Lost Credibility</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovak Cardinal Frantisek Tomasek
said in an interview published Saturday that the Czechoslovak
government lost credibility when it broke up a peaceful
demonstration for religious freedom last week.
   The Roman Catholic cardinal was quoted in the Austrian daily
Kurier as saying that the demonstration in Bratislava March 25
``was a step towards more religious freedom and the government must
take this into account.''
   Eyewitnesses estimated about 2,000 Roman Catholics took part in
the protest on Bratislava's downtown Hviezdoslav Square. Officials
said 125 people were arrested and later released. Riot police and
water cannons broke up the demonstration, which had been banned in
advance.
   ``The Czechoslovak government, through this measure, lost even
more credibility,'' Tomasek was quoted as saying in early Sunday
editions.
   Tomasek, 88, said the Roman Catholic Church is 99 percent
laymen. ``It is the duty of the laymen to demonstrate for their
rights,'' he was quoted as saying.
   The Slovak Communist Party daily Pravda charged Saturday that
the organizers of the demonstration were interested in the church
and religious freedom ``only as long as they can misuse them
politically against the socialist state.''
   According to the Czechoslovak state news agency CTK which
carried parts of the editorial, Pravda said religious activists
intended to harm talks between the Czechoslovak leadership and the
Vatican on filling 10 vacant Bishoprics.
   Tomasek complained in the Kurier interview that the Czechoslovak
delegation which is to travel to the Vatican for the next round of
negotiations later this month was ``negotiating in Rome about us,
but without us.'' The paper said Czechoslovak authorities had not
allowed him to take part.
   Austrian Cardinal Franz Koenig, in a seperate interview with
Kurier, praised the strength of religious belief in the East bloc.
   ``What the believers in these countries want _ and the Pope
supports them in this _ is not an upset of the political relations,
but the possibility as Christians to live their beliefs in a state
system which is officially based on atheism,'' Koenig was quoted as
saying.
   The former Archbishop of Vienna said he thought Pope John Paul
II's visit to Austria in June would be a ``bridge between East and
West in Europe.''
   ``What the Pope says in Austria will also be heard in
Yugoslavia, in Czechoslovakia and beyond and will be followed with
interest,'' Koenig was quoted as saying in the Kurier interview.
   Thousands of Hungarian and Slovene Catholics are expected to
come to Austria to see the Pope.
</TEXT>
