<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Meese-Richardson     04-02 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Richardson,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Attorney General Calls for Current Attorney General To Step
Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Meese Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Attorney General Elliot Richardson, a
casualty of the ``Saturday Night Massacre'' in 1973, added his
voice on Saturday to those calling for Attorney General Edwin Meese
III to step down.
   Richardson said on Cable News Network's ``Newsmaker Saturday''
program that Meese ``has forfeited confidence'' and should resign.
   ``Too many questions'' have been raised, he said, and Meese
``was too close to too many questionable dealings,'' which are
being investigated by an independent counsel.
   Richardson resigned on Oct. 20, 1973, a Saturday, after refusing
to carry out an order from President Nixon to fire special
prosecutor Archibald Cox. At the time, Cox was investigating the
White House's involvement in the Watergate scandal.
   Richardson said that as a private citizen, Meese is entitled to
full protection of the law, just as any citizen is. But, he said
that as the nation's chief law enforcement official, Meese must be
held to a higher standard.
   ``It is absolutely vital that there be maintained the highest
possible public confidence in the integrity of the Department'' of
Justice, Richardson said.
   Independent counsel James McKay is investigating Meese's conduct
in connection with a $1 billion Iraqi pipeline project and a
possible conflict of interest involving Meese's telephone company
stock.
   McKay said Friday he had insufficient evidence to date to
warrant indicting Meese in either case, but the investigation is
continuing.
</TEXT>
