<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ethiopia-Rebels     04-02 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia-Rebels,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebel Group Says It Controls Route for Famine Aid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Ethiopian rebel group claimed Saturday
that it controls the main route for transporting food for millions
of Ethiopians facing starvation.
   Assefa Mamoa, spokesman for the Tigre People's Liberation Front,
said the road between the northernmost provinces of Tigre and
Eritrea ``is only open for humanitarian assistance.''
   ``We are calling upon the humanitarian organizations to go on
with their operations and the TPLF will guarantee their security,''
he said in a telephone call from Washington to The Associated Press
bureau in Nairobi.
   Mamoa said the front took control of the road Thursday. The
rebels' claims could not be verified, but the Soviet-backed Marxist
government in the Ethiopian capital, Addis Ababa, has acknowledged
the rebels made some advances amid heavy fighting.
   Tigre and Eritrea are the worst-hit areas in a drought that has
threatened about 7 million Ethiopians with starvation. Fighting in
both regions has disrupted emergency relief efforts.
   Because of rebel activities, the government often closes roads
in the regions, cutting off truck convoys carrying food. Most of
the food reaching Tigre comes in by road after being unloaded at
the Eritrean port of Massawa on the Red Sea.
   David Morton, director of Ethiopian operations for the World
Food Program, said a U.N. convoy used the road Monday to deliver
food to the town of Wukro and returned along the same road Tuesday.
He said both trips were without incident.
   Mamoa also claimed that government troops on Thursday abandoned
the northern Tigre town of Adigrat. The front previously announced
the capture Thursday of the towns of Axum and Adowa.
   ``The only remaining major areas held by the Ethiopian
government are the (provincial) capital, Makelle, and Maichew,''
Mamoa said. ``The situation of the Ethiopian military forces is
collapsing.''
   Ethiopian President Mengistu Haile Mariam said in a radio
broadcast Thursday that his troops were fighting ``grim battles''
against secessionist rebels in Tigre and Eritrea. It was a rare
acknowledgement.
   Mengistu inherited the insurgencies 13 years ago when he and a
group of fellow army officers dethroned Emperor Haile Selassie and
set up a Marxist government.
   Eritrean rebels have been fighting for 27 years in Africa's
oldest civil war. The civil war in Tigre is in its 14th year.
</TEXT>
