<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ArmTroubles     04-02 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arm Troubles,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guardsman Faces Court-Martial Over Rolling up Sleeves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A National Guardsman spent a night in
jail and faces a court-martial over what he says was his inability
to roll up his sleeves because his arms are too big.
   Ronald Brown, a muscular Escambia County Utilities Authority
meter reader in civilian life, was arrested Thursday by sheriff's
deputies on a warrant for failing to appear at a Feb. 23
court-martial.
   Capt. James Welsh, who will preside over the court-martial, said
he doesn't think Brown is telling everything he did wrong. Brown is
charged with disobeying an order.
   ``Think to yourself, there's got to be more to it,'' Welsh said.
Guard officials ``aren't that thin-skinned.''
   Brown, who was released Friday on orders of his battalion
commander, said he was told to roll his sleeves up while taking
down tents following an exercise last November. Brown said he was
unable to comply because his arms were too big for his shirtsleeves.
   He said that a month later he was accused by a lieutenant of
willfully disobeying an order and asked if he would voluntarily
accept an unspecified punishment. Brown said he refused and asked
to speak to a higher authority.
   He said he didn't hear anything more about it until February
when a clerk mentioned a hearing in his case, but he insisted he
never received formal notification of the court-martial.
   The Guard says three registered mail notices were sent to him.
   ``If they say I got three notices they must have been delivered
to the wrong mailbox,'' Brown said. ``The National Guard should
have just given me a phone call to tell me about the court-martial.
They've got my number.''
   Capt. Gary Griffith, commander of the 417th Signal Battalion,
said Brown failed to go to the post office to pick up the
registered letters and that he suspected the part-time soldier knew
what was in the envelopes.
   Griffith rescheduled the court-martial for May 19.
</TEXT>
