<1ST_LINE>r a AM-China-Wine     04-02 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Wine,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Might Join Foreign Ownersship of California Wineries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If officials in China can work out the
details, a Chinese-owned winery next year might join the growing
lineup of foreign-owned California wineries.
   ``So far China has never had a winery outside of China; we have
to make research first,'' Guo Song-Quon, chief winemaker of a
leading Chinese winery, said Friday through an interpreter.
   Guo's place of business is Tianjin's 80,000-case-a-year Heavenly
Palace Winery south of Beijing.
   Heavenly Palace has been marketing its ``Spring Moon'' brand in
the United States since September, mostly in Chinese restaurants.
The wine, a medium-dry, fruity muscat, is the only export label in
the Heavenly Palace line.
   China has been making an intensive effort to earn foreign
exchange as fast as possible, and a quality California winery _
participating in a strong premium wine boom _ would help in that
direction.
   At last count, there were 39 foreign-owned wineries out of about
650 in California.
   If the Chinese join the lineup, their foreign colleagues in this
state would include British, five wineries; Canadians, seven;
French, 11; West Germans, two; Belgians, one; Swiss, five; Spanish,
two; Japanese, five; and Thais, 1.
   Guo, the son of Guo Qichang, China's senior winemaker and a top
official of the China's Ministry of Light Industry, has been on a
whirlwind tour of California wineries this week, he said in an
interview.
   ``I will make a full report that will go back to the Chinese
government,'' said Guo, who has visited wineries in the Sonoma,
Napa and Central valleys. He expressed admiration for the
California style of winemaking.
   Especially under study, said Guo, is the American system of
wine-marketing.
   ``What is marketing?'' he said, expressing the question as a
statement. ``In China, we don't understand marketing ... even
bottling ... we have a lot of problems with bottling in China;
there is nothing modern like in California. We want China to follow
the American (wine) system.''
   Through an interpreter, Guo said preliminary plans for Chinese
investment in California wine call for an operation independent of
the government, with home winery funds and dollars borrowed from
U.S. banks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
