<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru   04-02 0882</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0571,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Blames Arab Leaders for Lack of Peace</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Dukakis delivering speech
and disagreement with Jackson; picks up 6th graf pvs, bgng: First,
on...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSHKOSH, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential hopeful Michael
Dukakis on Saturday blamed Arab leaders for the failure of Middle
East peace initiatives and said he disagreed strongly with Jesse
Jackson on policies in the region.
   Positioning himself for the crucial New York primary in two
weeks, the Massachusetts governor said that the question of a
Palestinian homeland should be resolved in the direct negotiations
between Israel and its neighbors.
   ``We will reach out to those on all sides, in all countries, who
believe in a future of peace and security,'' Dukakis said in a
major foreign policy speech before about 600 people at the
University of Wisconsin at Oshkosh. ``Negotiations with the
Palestinian people are possible. Negotiations with terrorists are
not.''
   Dukakis has been reluctant to point out where he disagrees with
rival Jesse Jackson on the issues, but he did so when asked about
Jackson's embrace of PLO leader Yasser Arafat and whether the PLO
and Israel are ``morally equivalent.
   ``I don't agree with him,'' Dukakis said.
   That relatively mild statement contrasted sharply with Sen.
Albert Gore Jr.'s denunciation of Jackson's foreign policy ideas in
the same area earlier this week.
   With the speech and a later news conference, Dukakis was trying
to make certain that rival presidential hopeful Gore does not
appear more committed to Israel than he does _ a key issue with
Jewish voters who may make up a quarter of the New York electorate.
   Aides denied the speech was designed to respond to Gore but
admitted it should blunt the controversy about Gore's comments.
   On another matter, Dukakis said the United States has the full
right to defend the Panama Canal, and that he does not oppose
President Reagan's dispatch of more troops there in light of the
unrest in Panama.
   First on Saturday, Dukakis turned his attention to blue-collar
voters in the Wisconsin primary on Tuesday. At a labor roundtable
in Kenosha, his approach was a combination of competence and
earthiness.
   ``My friends, this is not a lot of talk. I know how to do
things,'' the Massachusetts governor told the crowd. ``After seven
years of charisma, maybe it is time we had a little competence in
the White House.''
   Twice in his speech, Dukakis used an expletive, an unusual
action for a politican with a repuation as a controlled technocrat.
   ``Hell, I'm the only candidate in this race who has ever
balanced a budget,'' he said at one point.
   Then boasting about the benefits of full employment, Dukakis
added: ``Hell, they are paying six bucks an hour in McDonalds in my
state, because they can't get people. It's a wonderful, wonderful
thing. That's the kind of future I want to build for this country.''
   In his foreign policy speech, Dukakis touched on a range of
issues, but the biggest chunk dealt with the Middle East.
   Dukakis called for a continuation of the Camp David peace
process, which he said was the ``unfulfilled'' vision of the late
Egyptian President Anwar Sadat and former Israeli Prime Minister
Menachem Begin.
   ``Why? Because few Arab leaders have had the courage to see the
Middle East as Sadat saw it. Few Arab leaders have had the wisdom
to choose reconciliation over conflict, to choose hope instead of
hate; to prepare for the future rather than relive the wars of the
past,'' he said.
   Dukakis made abundantly clear his commitment to Israel.
   ``The first thing anyone must understand about the Middle East
is that we will never let Israel down,'' he said . ``For decades,
America leaders have know and the American people have understood,
that Israel's fate is our fate ... that our security interests are
linked and that our historical and cultural bonds cannot and will
not broken.
   ``Israel _ like the United States _ is a special place.''
   After support for Israel, Dukakis laid down three other tenets
of his Middle East policy.
   The second was the necessity for direct negotiations between
Israel and its neighbors.
   Third was a continuation of the Camp David understandings on the
future of the West Bank and the Gaza strip.
   ``That framework recognizes the right of the people of the
territories to shape their own destiny in a way that is consistent
with Israel's right to exist within safe and security and
recognized borders,'' he said.
   And fourth, Dukakis condemned the Soviet Union and China for
continuing a major flow of arms into the Middle East, particularly
China's sale of medium-range missiles to Saudi Arabia.
   Dukakis did not mention his dispute with Gore over a letter 30
U.S. senators signed on March 3, encouraging Secretary of State
George Shultz to pursue his peace plan and criticizing Israeli
leaders for not cooperating with the effort.
   On Central America, Dukakis praised the progress toward peace in
the region, castigating the Reagan administration for being unable
to ``cope with the threat of peace'' there.
   Dukakis also brought up U.S. policy toward South Africa where he
declared the president must ``say `no' to apartheid; `no' to
racism; ``no to doing business with South Africa.''
</TEXT>
