<2ND_LINE>AM-Libya Defector,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports Libyan officer defected to anti-Gadhafi organization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An organization of Libyan exiles opposed to
Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi said Saturday an army officer
had defected and denounced ``Gadhafi's bloody rule.''
   The statement was distributed by the Cairo-based National Front
for the Salvation of Libya _ NFSL.
   It said Libyan Lt. Col. Abdallah Ahmed Khaled al-Sheikhy had
joined the NFSL because it is ``the honorable force struggling to
overthrow Gahafi's bloody rule.''
   The statement was not signed by the officer and there was no way
to independently verity the claim.
   The NFSL has reported two other defections of Libyan colonels in
the past nine days, but did not say where the officers were.
   A Salvation of Libya statement on March 30 was signed by Col.
Saleh Mohammed and said he had joined the NFSL.
   Five days earlier, a statement said the chief of Libya's forces
in Chad, Col. Khalifah Abu el-Kassem Haftar, had defected to the
NFSL. The statement gave no details but an NFSL spokesman said
Haftar had been a prisoner of war in Chad.
   Libya claims a large zone of northern Chad and the dispute has
provoked frequent battles between the North African neighbors.
Gadhafi also backs Chadian rebel forces.
