<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LostBridge     04-02 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lost Bridge,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Dakota Looks For Caretaker For `Lost Bridge'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB IMRIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANDAREE, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 500-foot highway of steel over the
Little Missouri River is more than just a bridge to this small
village on the Fort Berthold Indian Reservation.
   This one possesses personality, they say, so much so they refer
to it by name _ Lost Bridge.
   The 20-foot-wide, three-span truss bridge was erected in 1929
when it only connected two dusty cattle trails, said Bill Jennings,
assistant bridge engineer for the state Highway Department.
   ``They built a bridge that had no access to it,'' said Lisa
Redford, a spokesman for Mandaree Inc.
   Now that state Highway 22 crosses the bridge, the state wants to
build a replacement, and Mandaree Inc. hopes to preserve the old
span as a focus for development.
   People old enough to remember its origin are still baffled. ``I
don't even know why they built it,'' Fred Lone Fight said.
   Nobody used Lost Bridge before Garrison Dam was built downstream
in the 1950s and Lake Sakakawea blocked many roads, Pamela Black
Hawk recalled.
   Eventually, Highway 22 became a paved ribbon of asphalt and the
bridge, part of the shortest western route around the lake, got far
more use. The state wants to replace it with a modern bridge that's
16 feet wider and can carry heavier loads, Jennings said.
   So the state is searching for a buyer for the steel structure
and is offering $50,000 to aid in moving it. If no one takes the
bridge, it will be torn down.
   Mandaree Inc. is exploring the possibility of essentially
adopting the bridge. The group envisions using it for a fishing
site, the focal point of a place for prairie-weary travelers to
stop for rest or a picnic, said Redford.
   That would preserve Lost Bridge for its historic and sentimental
importance, she said.
   The bridge sits 10 miles south of Mandaree in a picturesque
valley of rolling river bluffs that are void of any man-made
structures except for the highway itself and an occasional highway
sign.
   Driving into the valley, the sun-drenched metal bridge glistens
as it stands against a backdrop of prairie grass.
   Any group that agrees to preserve the bridge gets at least
$50,000 _ the estimated expense for tearing it down _ from the
state, Jennings said.
   The deadline for assuming ownership of bridge is November, he
said. Mandaree Inc. hopes to make a decision within the next few
weeks, Redford said.
   ``We are looking right now into the liabilities and what the
federal guidelines call for in maintaining a (historic) bridge,''
said Redford.
   ``The history is what makes it unique,'' Jennings said. ``The
fact they call it a lost bridge.''
   A new bridge just west of Lost Bridge will cost an estimated $1
million, he said. The state hopes to begin construction in 1990.
   In the early 1970s, the state tried to give away a rainbow-arch
bridge over the Cannonball River but found no takers, Jennings
recalled.
   ``They took a lot of pictures, wrote up quite a documentary on
it, and destroyed the bridge,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
