<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Congress     04-02 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Congress,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Announces Election Procedures That Permit More Candidates
Than Seats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's legislature blew a small breath of
democracy into the government on Saturday by approving a bill that
for the first time allows candidates to compete for seats on its
standing committee.
   From now on, the 2,794 delegates to the National People's
Congress will elect its 155-member standing committee.
   As before, 20 candidates, including the chairman and vice
chairmen, will be chosen by the Congress' ruling Presidium and
elected without opposition, but now 144 candidates will compete for
the other 135 seats.
   Deputies can vote against a candidate or abstain, but the 20
without opposition can be defeated only if they get fewer than half
of votes cast.
   Only two delegates opposed and one abstained in the vote to
approve the procedure.
   The Congress ruled out more than one candidate for such posts as
president and vice president, Congress chairman, chairman of the
Central Military Commission and president of the Supreme People's
Court.
   It said the Presidium will fill those key posts ``in line with
the opinions of the majority of deputies.''
   The Presidium will also elect the premier, vice premiers,
ministers, state councilors and other government officers, with a
single candidate for each post submitted by the president.
   Acting Premier Li Peng is certain to be formally named head of
government.
   China says the current session of the Congress has been the most
open and democratic ever. Official newspapers and national
television have spotlighted debate among the delegates and speeches
voicing opposition to various policies.
   Still, the Communist Party and its governing Politburo remain in
firm control over decisions of policy and personnel. The Congress'
main function is still to rubber-stamp moves by the party.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
