<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru   04-02 0768</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0531,0788</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Says It Crushes Kurdish-Iranian Offensive</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Iraq saying it may continue missile truce,
INSERT two grafs after 5th graf pvs: A tenuous .... Pick up 6th
graf pvs: Kuwait's ruler...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said Saturday its forces killed
thousands of Iranian troops and overran bases of Iranian-backed
Kurdish rebels in mountainous northeastern Iraq.
   Iranian warplanes bombed an Iraqi garrison in the region, Tehran
radio reported, but Iran's news media had no immediate comment on
the Iraqi victory claim.
   Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency reported that Iraqi forces
were leveling the Kurdish town of Seyyed Sadiq in Sulaymaniyah
province and its inhabitants were seeking refuge in nearby towns.
   Kurdish separatist leader Jalal Talabani confirmed there was
heavy fighting and said Iraq was ``waging a genocide campaign
against our people through the daily use of poison gas.''
   A tenuous halt in the ``war of the cities'' held as Iraq
continued to silence its long-range missile launchers for the
duration of a trip to Baghdad by Turkish Prime Minister Turgut
Ozal. Iran did not report any attacks on civilian targets either.
   Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz reaffirmed his nation's
readiness to continue the halt even after Ozal returns to Turkey,
probably Sunday evening, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
   But it quoted him as saying the truce would continue only if
Iran accepted several Iraqi demands, including an Iranian
withdrawal from Iraqi territory, that Iran has repeatedly scoffed
at.
   Kuwait's ruler issued a new appeal to Iran to end the war with
Iraq through negotiations.
   Baghdad radio quoted a high command communique as saying Iraqi
troops ``completely purged'' the area around Qara Dagh in the
Sulaymaniyah region of Iraq in the last two weeks.
   Qala Dagh is only 20 miles west of Lake Darbandikhan, where
Iranian Revolutionary Guards have thrust into Iraq in a 16-day-old
offensive.
   The Iraqi News Agency quoted its correspondent as saying
thousands of Iranians were killed. He did not give figures for
casualties among the Kurdish guerrillas.
   The correspondent also specifically denied a report, carried
Friday by The Associated Press, that Kurdish rebels were within
five miles of a major highway linking Sulaymaniyah with other Iraqi
cities.
   The communique quoted by Baghdad radio said ``all traitors have
finally been destroyed,'' in a reference to the Iranian-backed
Kurdish rebels who have been fighting Baghdad for an independent
homeland for years.
   It said an Iraqi force, including Kurdish fighters loyal to
Baghdad, had overrun 21 Kurdish bases and villages used by the
guerrillas in the last few days.
   Tehran radio said Iranian warplanes bombed an Iraqi garrison at
Shanandari, in the heart of the area of hostilities, ``inflicting
heavy losses and damage.''
   Talabani, leader of one of the two main Kurdish rebel groups,
the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan, said an Iraqi chemical attack on
the village of Seo-o-Saru earlier last week killed 60 Kurdish
villagers and wounded 211.
   ``They are now resorting to a scorched-earth policy, killing
defenseless women and children indiscriminately and destroying
whole villages,'' he said in London on Friday.
   IRNA reported that Iranian troops who were nearby heard
``several huge explosions'' coming from Seyyed Sadiq on Saturday
and ``many buildings in the Iraqi town have been demolished.''
   It said groups of inhabitants were escaping from the town to
nearby towns and villages.
   Massud Barzani, leader of the other big rebel group, the Kurdish
Democratic Party, had said several days ago that the Iraqi army
launched a major offensive against the guerrillas March 23.
   He said two divisions of troops, backed by tanks, artillery and
air strikes, were seeking to dislodge rebel fighters and their
allies, the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan, from the Qara Dagh
mountains between Kirkuk and the provincial capital of Sulaymaniyah.
   An Iraqi division usually numbers about 12,000 men.
   The villages are north of the Iranian bridgehead around Lake
Darbandikhan, where Iran claims Iraqi chemical bombing attacks
March 16-17 on ``liberated'' Kurdish towns killed 5,000 civilians
and injured 5,000 more.
   Kuwait's ruler, Sheik Jaber al-Ahmed al-Sabah, said in an
address at the inauguration of the sixth conference of Arab justice
ministers, ``Judging by Islamic and Arab history, we find that
inter-Islamic wars did not provide any radical solution to
problems.''
   He called on Iran ``to abide by the Islamic teachings, stick to
good neighborliness and accept reconciliation and dialogue instead
of aggression and the continuation of war and destruction.''
   Sheik Jaber's peace appeal came only three days after three
Iranian gunboats opened fire on a military post on Kuwait's Bubiyan
Island, wounding two Kuwaiti soldiers.
</TEXT>
