<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 1627EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Philippines-Military     04-02 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Military,0668</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Escape Raises New Doubts About Filipino Military, Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Philippines</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The daring prison escape of the
leader of the August coup attempt raised new doubts about military
leadership under President Corazon Aquino's government.
   The flight Saturday of former Lt. Col. Gregorio ``Gringo''
Honasan, with 14 prison guards from an elite navy unit, came four
days after the military boasted of the arrest of seven top
communist rebels.
   ``How was it possible, because he was on a ship and under
guard?'' Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile said of the escape. ``How could it
happen?''
   Honasan, 39, served as security chief when Enrile, now an
opposition leader, was minister of defense.
   Before dawn Saturday, Honasan fled the prison ship where he had
been held since his capture in December. The 14 officers from the
navy's special warfare unit were supposed to be guarding him, but
they fled with him.
   Honasan and the guards escaped under gunfire from other guards
and reached shore in two rubber dinghies a few hundred yards from
navy headquarters.
   In what may be worse for the military's image, spokesman Col.
Oscar Florendo acknowledged the armed forces learned last week of a
possible escape attempt and had doubled the guard force on the
ship. The dinghies had come with the increased security.
   Mrs. Aquino announced Saturday that the vessel's commander, Lt.
Cmdr. Fred Tuvilla, had been arrested and may face court-martial
for negligence.
   She also threatened to punish any soldiers who help Honasan. He
and other military dissidents were responsible for six major coup
plots against her government.
   Florendo said Honasan was apt to try to organize new plots
against the government and to divide the 160,000-member military.
The charismatic former colonel remains widely admired in the
military even though he was dismissed after his Aug. 28 coup
attempt left at least 53 people dead.
   His escape was widely reported Saturday in the Filipino media,
which normally curtail operations on Easter weekend. Scores of
callers to Manila radio stations questioned how Honasan could have
escaped without the help of the guards.
   Military Chief of Staff Gen. Renato de Villa told reporters
Saturday he accepted responsibility for the escape but would let
Mrs. Aquino decide whether he should be relieved.
   ``Somehow, in one way or another, I bear responsibility for
ensuring that our detainees are secured and procedures are
followed,'' he said.
   Last month, the congressional Commission on Appointments
approved de Villa's nomination as chief of staff.
   The move came despite opposition from some congressmen who felt
the former Constabulary commander should have retired instead.
Critics said extending his tour of duty limited promotion of
younger officers and smacked of practices under ousted President
Ferdinand Marcos.
   The escape also raised doubts whether the congressional
commission would approve the recent nomination of Adm. Carlito
Cunanan, former chief of the Coast Guard, as navy commander.
   Congressional sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
they already had misgivings about Cunanan because of the Coast
Guard's inept handling of rescue efforts in a December collision of
a Filipino passenger ship and oil tanker that killed 3,000 people.
   The escape took place as the military was enjoying new prestige
for Tuesday's arrest of seven leading communists, including Romulo
Kintanar, commander of the rebel New People's Army.
   Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos had said the arrests showed that
the military had overcome past divisions and could now act
effectively.
   But on Saturday, he called the escape ``disturbing news.''
   De Villa said the search for Honasan, moreover, would divert
military resources from the fight against the rebels.
   One Filipino politician also worried about the international
impact of Honasan's escape. Sen. John Osmena said it was bound to
tarnish the government's image abroad and raise more doubts about
the stability of the Aquino administration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
