<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GermanyMarches     04-02 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany Marches,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Join in annual Easter marches against nuclear weapons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of West Germans
joined Saturday in the annual Easter weekend marches to demand the
elimination of all nuclear weapons and the closure of nuclear power
plants.
   Organizers said marches were held in all of the nation's major
cities and there also were vigils near the sites where two jet
fighters of West Germany's allies crashed last week.
   No estimate of the number of people participating in the marches
was given. Police reported the demonstrations were peaceful.
   A French Mirage jet crashed Wednesday within a mile of a nuclear
power plant in Bavaria state, killing the pilot.
   A U.S. Air Force F-16 fighter crashed into the small town of
Forst on Thursday and the pilot and a resident were killed.
   The F-16 went down about eight miles from a nuclear power
station. Officials said such crashes posed no danger of an accident
at nuclear power facilities because thick concrete domes shield the
reactors.
   March organizers said more anti-nuclear demonstrations will be
held Sunday.
</TEXT>
