<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-02 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Drenches Central Gulf Coast, Deep Snow On Western Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm centered over Kansas spread rain and thunderstorms up
and down the Mississippi Valley on Saturday, causing floods and
tornadoes in Louisiana and trailing heavy snow across the western
Great Plains.
   Heavy rain accompanied showers and thunderstorms across southern
Louisiana into southern Alabama during the morning.
   Widespread street flooding was reported across the New Orleans
area and north of Lake Pontchartrain. Rainfall amounts in the New
Orleans area ranged up to 9 inches since Friday evening, with 8.17
inches at Gretna and 6.09 inches at Gramercy. In east-central
Louisiana, 5.65 inches fell at Bayou Sorrel.
   During the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST, 2.08 inches of rain fell
at New Orleans' Lakefront Airport.
   Strong thunderstorms developed during the afternoon across parts
of eastern Iowa and northwestern Illinois. Showers were scattered
from western Nebraska through southern Minnesota and northern
Illinois, with most rain amounts less than an inch.
   Snow and blowing snow made travel difficult in northwestern
Kansas and northeastern Colorado, and most roads in the western two
counties of the Oklahoma Panhandle were closed.
   Snow amounts included 13 inches at Goodland, Kan.; 22 at Timpas,
Colo.; 20 at Walsh, Colo.; and up to 23 inches in the Oklahoma
Panhandle, according to highway officials and the National Weather
Service.
   Drifts 4 to 5 feet high and wind gusting to 40 mph were reported
across southeastern Colorado, the weeather service said.
   Elsewhere, showers were scattered across the Pacific Northwest
as another storm system approached the coast.
   Showers were scattered across parts of eastern Georgia extending
into northeastern Florida. Showers also developed over parts of the
upper Ohio Valley.
   Dense morning fog slowed travel across northern Illinois and
southern Wisconsin into northern Indiana.
   The fog halted landings at Chicago's O'Hare airport for about
two hours early in the morning, said Joe Hopkins of United
Airlines, the airport's largest carrier. By 9:30 a.m., when
visibility was about a quarter of a mile at O'Hare, United had
cancelled about 90 flights out of 800 scheduled because of the fog,
he said.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 33
degrees at Imperial, Neb., to 86 at Thermal, Calif. The low for the
day was 10 degrees at Lake Yellowstone, Wyo.
   For Sunday, widespread showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from the Great Lakes through the Ohio and Tennessee valleys to the
central Gulf of Mexico coast. Widespread showers also were forecast
over the northern Pacific Coast with scattered showers inland.
   Highs in the 40s were predicted from northeastern Minnesota into
Upper Michigan; in the 50s across south-central and eastern
Colorado, the upper Mississippi Valley, the upper Great Lakes and
much of New England, and across the Pacific Northwest; in the 80s
from the desert Southwest across southern Texas into the lower
Mississippi Valley, and across much of the Florida Peninsula; and
in the 60s or 70s across much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
