<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mecham     04-02 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham,0639</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Impeachment Verdict Won't End Arizona's Legal Morass</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This week's expected verdict in Gov. Evan
Mecham's impeachment trial won't necessarily end the legal morass
that surrounds the Arizona governorship.
   The Senate plans to vote Monday or Tuesday on whether Mecham, a
first-term Republican, should be the first Arizona governor removed
from office.
   Senators heard five weeks of testimony on allegations that
Mecham misused $80,000 in state money by loaning it to his auto
dealership, and that he tried to thwart an investigation of an
alleged death threat by a state official.
   With 20 of the 30 Senate votes required for conviction, nobody
is predicting what will happen.
   If he is acquitted, Mecham will automatically regain the
gubernatorial powers he gave up to Acting Gov. Rose Mofford, the
Democratic secretary of state, when he was impeached by the House
Feb. 5.
   If the Senate convicts him on either count, Mecham will be
removed from office immediately.
   In either event, the matter won't necessarily end there.
   If acquitted, Mecham faces two more battles to keep the
governorship.
   A criminal trial is due to start April 21 on a charge similar to
one impeachment charge the Senate dropped: failure to report a
$350,000 campaign loan. The governor faces six felony counts of
fraud, perjury and filing false documents, and his brother and 1986
campaign treasurer, Willard Mecham, faces three similar counts.
   Senators who voted to drop the impeachment count said they
feared that if they heard evidence on the charge it would
jeopardize Mecham's right to a fair trial.
   If convicted in the criminal trial, Mecham would be removed from
office automatically and could face up to 22 years in prison.
   Mecham also is running against six candidates in a recall
election May 17. Polls vary widely, with some showing him far
behind but one putting Mecham and Mrs. Mofford in a dead heat for
first place.
   If the Senate votes to oust him, the governor and his defense
attorney, Jerris Leonard, say they could appeal to the U.S. Supreme
Court on grounds that Mecham's constitutional rights were violated.
   It's also unclear whether the May 17 recall must be held if the
state Senate convicts Mecham on the impeachment charges.
   Attorney General Bob Corbin, a Republican, said Friday he
believes the recall still must be held because the Arizona
Constitution says a recall is aimed at the office, not the
officeholder.
   However, Corbin said he philosophically opposes holding the
recall if Mecham has already been removed.
   ``I don't think our founding fathers who drafted the
Constitution ever dreamed we would be in this position,'' he said.
   This and other remaining legal questions should be settled in
court, Corbin said.
   If the recall were to go ahead following a Senate conviction,
officials say it's also unclear whether Mecham would be allowed to
run.
   He has an automatic spot on the ballot, but Paul Bender, dean of
the Arizona State University law school, argues that a Senate vote
to remove him would apply to the entire four-year term and he could
not remain in office even if he won the recall vote.
   Legal questions surround Mrs. Mofford's gubernatorial candidacy
too. A campaign was formed to draft her because Arizona's ``resign
to run'' law apparently would require her to quit as acting
governor and secretary of state if she declared her candidacy.
   A court challenge has been mounted to see if the Mofford draft
campaign was handled properly, without any involvement by the
intended candidate.
   Corbin said his office warned years ago that the laws were
unclear and should be straightened out, ``and nobody has, so here
we are.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
