<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DaytonaBreak     04-02 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Daytona Break,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spring Break at Easter: Beer and Bibles Co-Exist at Beach</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Operation Sonshine in 4th graf is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While suds, sun and sin may prevail
among much of the spring break throngs on the wide beaches of
Daytona this Easter weekend, morning devotions replace hangovers in
at least three beach hotels.
   Daytona Beach has become a mecca for spring break in recent
years, and an estimated 500,000 students descend on the area to
forget classwork and laze in the sun. But it's not all rowdy
parties and promiscuity.
   At the beachfront El Caribe Hotel, students carry Bibles through
the lobby. The hotel caters to members of the Campus Crusade for
Christ, a national interdenominational group.
   ``You can only get so drunk and sunburned and bored,'' said
Cliff Mills, director of Operation Sonshine of the Campus Crusade.
``A lot of them want to know more about Christ.''
   Mills, whose organization has conducted conferences for some
3,000 students during spring break, said Campus Crusade members
take their Gospel message to the beach in the afternoons and that
sun worshipers are often receptive.
   El Caribe does not allow unchaperoned non-member students under
21 to rent rooms during spring break.
   ``The difference is day and night,'' said El Caribe owner Mary
Ann Richardson, explaining how students in her hotel act compared
with students staying at the dozens of other beach hotels.
   Ms. Richardson said the biggest problem in her hotel is minor
noise making, and that the students are generally well-behaved and
polite.
   The situation was much the same at The Desert Inn and the High
Seas Motel, also spring break gathering places for Campus Crusade
members.
   ``There was no muss, no fuss and no beer-bottle throwing,'' said
Anne Madorsky, a part-owner of the Desert Inn, the Voyager and
Americana hotels.
   Many of the crowds at Daytona used to go to Fort Lauderdale
before that community began to try to change its image with
stricter law enforcement.
   Officials in Fort Lauderdale have estimated their crowds will
range between 100,000 and 200,000 this year, compared with 350,000
in 1985.
   Daytona officials say this spring break, students generally have
behaved better than in the past, when hotel guests tossed such
objects as unopened beer cans, room chairs and even rollaway beds
from balconies.
   So far this year, there have been two spring break fatalities in
Daytona, one a 24-year-old man, not a student, who fell from a
balcony, the other a 21-year-old student who was hit by a car.
   There were five other balcony falls this year in Daytona, but
only two of the six involved students and most resulted in only
minor injuries. In the past three years, six deaths have resulted
from balcony accidents.
   In the Florida Panhandle, two spring break visitors were
hospitalized after balcony falls Friday in Destin, a Gulf Coast
resort town.
   David Jeffers, 26, of Atlanta, fell while doing pullups from a
fifth-floor balcony railing, authorities said. He was listed in
guarded condition at Humana Hospital in Fort Walton Beach.
   David McGee, 18, of Baton Rouge, who fell three floors, was in
stable condition at the same hospital.
   Evelyn Fine, executive director of the Mid-Florida Research and
Business Center of Daytona Beach Community College, said some
500,000 students have come to Daytona for spring break this year
and 330,000 will have lodged in a hotel for an average stay of
about five days.
   She predicted that each student spends an average of $375, not
including transportation, for a direct-dollar impact of $123.7
million on the Daytona Beach economy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880402-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 1711EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0581 04-02 0709</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0581,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama's Easter Joy Dampened by Crisis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts 2d graf to clarify that packets contained incense</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The incense vendor accepted a poor
woman's coins and spooned tiny measures of powdered red sandalwood,
honey-crystal myrrh and dried rosemary into scraps of paper.
   ``Thirty cents,'' lamented Miguel Valencia, appraising the three
dimes paid for the incense. ``This is the worst year ever.''
   The tall, ebony-skinned man, who peddles crosses and other piety
objects, said he has sold only a $1 portrait of Jesus Christ since
midweek.
   Holy Week is usually the best time of year for Valencia and the
small business he runs from a rickety stand in front of the
Metropolitan Cathedral. Indeed, the Easter holiday usually brings
joy throughout this country where about 95 percent of 2.2 million
people are Roman Catholic.
   But an economic and social crisis over the rule of military
chief Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega has cast a pall over this year's
celebration.
   Gen. Noriega, under drug-trafficking charges in the United
States, has moved to consolidate control despite increasing U.S.
pressure on him to step down and leave the country.
   He closed banks a month ago to prevent a cash panic after
Washington froze Panamanian assets in the United States. The
government has failed to pay most of its 130,000 workers, and
private employees have nowhere to cash their checks. The money
crisis worsened nationwide hunger and unemployment.
   Meanwhile, the U.S. government has been stepping up its military
presence in Panama, though administration officials say they don't
intend to use force to oust the strongman they once backed. Another
1,300 military personnel will arrive Tuesday, bringing to nearly
12,000 the number of U.S. troops there.
   The administration says the troops are intended to protect U.S.
bases and 45,000 Americans living in Panama.
   ``Never have we Panamanians lived a Lent with such tension,
division and increasing want in great sectors of the country,''
said a Catholic church statement. ``The people suffer and await the
Feast of the Resurrection, that it may signal some light of hope.''
   Few Panamanians saw cause for optimism. The church said Saturday
that opposition leaders had accepted a church role as mediator in
the country's travail. But the opposition continued to demand that
Noriega leave the country, something he has doggedly refused to do.
   Many people in the streets expressed despair over unremitting
price increases and hunger. Fresh fish, a typical Easter meal in
years past, has risen beyond modest means in this isthmus between
the Atlantic and Pacific oceans.
   Many hunkered down in the capital of Panama City, forgoing
customary visits with family in the provinces to protect
diminishing savings. Department of Transportation agent Roger
Chacon said outbound traffic through La Chorrera, the main gate to
the countryside, was extremely light all week.
   External calm replaced weeks of political activity and
demonstrations in Panama City. Police replaced the heavily armed
Defense Forces soldiers on the street Friday for the first time
since an unsuccessful March 16 coup attempt against Noriega.
   Five men conversed on 17th Street downtown. Two sat on a
workshop bench carried out to the sidewalk and three others stood
while all sipped a mixture of rum, milk and ice from paper cups.
   ``None of us would be here now if it weren't for the crisis,''
said a man in a sleeveless T-shirt and shorts. ``We'd be in
Chiriqui where it's cool.''
   The mountainous western province is a favorite tourist spot in
better times.
   ``So our recreation is conversation and a couple drinks,'' said
another in a blue ``guayabera,'' the loose-fitting tropical shirt.
   Inevitably, talk turned to the crisis. All five said they
opposed Noriega. One suggested that ``out of the 2 million
Panamanians, 200 support him.''
   Because of fear of reprisals, none wanted his name published.
   Some of the men also talked bitterly of how U.S. sanctions were
making their holiday and their lives difficult.
   ``Panama has been a good friend to the United States for more
than 80 years,'' said one. ``And it hurts more to be wounded by a
friend.''
   And all doubted that the population, stymied by government
repression, could do much to change things after the holiday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
