<DOCNO> AP880402-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 1722EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Divers-Families     04-02 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Divers-Families,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Families Await Word on Fate of Divers Held by Indonesia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The families of six California scuba divers
arrested in Indonesia nearly two weeks ago say they are still
anxiously awaiting word on whether the men will be charged with
crimes for allegedly entering restricted waters.
   Indonesian authorities suspect the six were seeking valuables
from a Dutch ship that sank more than 200 years ago, according to
Ruth van Heuven, a spokeswoman for the U.S. Bureau of Consular
Affairs in Washington, D.C.
   ``Our lives are at a standstill. We all live hooked to our
phones,'' said Jennifer Craft, wife of one of the men taken into
custody March 22 when Indonesian authorities boarded the boat they
chartered in Singapore.
   In addition to the six Californians, three Australians, a Briton
and an Iranian were also aboard the Budi Indah, according to Julie
Meldrum, an Australian Embassy spokeswoman.
   The divers are being held until the investigation is completed.
   Sophisticated sonar equipment found on the boat added to
authorities' suspicion about the group, Ms. van Heuven said.
   Joseph Yun, an American vice-consul in the North Sumatra capital
of Medan, said the detained Americans contended they were in
international waters.
   ``As of yet there have been no formal charges filed against the
divers,'' Ms. van Heuven said in an interview last week.
   ``They are in good condition and have no complaints about
maltreatment,'' said James Alleckson Brown, a U.S. embassy
spokesman in Jakarta.
   Mrs. Craft said Indonesian officials have told her the country
does not hold a person for more than 20 days without bringing
formal charges.
   U.S. and Australian embassy officials said last week they were
still trying to establish the facts surrounding the incident.
Indonesian officials in the Department of Communications, the
Foreign Office and the navy would not make any comment.
   One of the six, Cliff Craft, 43, a building inspector from
Whittier, faces misdemeanor charges in California in the pillaging
of an underwater wreck off Channel Islands National Park, said
Allan Gordon, a Ventura County deputy district attorney.
   Debi Commerford of Orange, the wife of another diver, said none
of the six in Indonesia was looking for treasure. She said her
husband, Danny, and Craft were there to start a building inspection
business in Singapore and to dive with the others for recreation.
   The others from California have been identified as Patrick
Gibson, 47, a systems analyst from Van Nuys; Jim Vorus of Santa
Monica, and Bob and Bruce Lanhan of Pleasant Hill.
</TEXT>
