<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EasterBunnies     04-02 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Easter Bunnies,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florist Says He May Halt Live Easter Bunny Display</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 60-year-old Easter tradition _ a sidewalk
display of live Easter bunnies _ may bow to protests and be gone
next year, the florist who sets it up said Saturday.
   ``It will be determined by the public. If they want us to have
the rabbits next year, we suggest that they write in to us,'' said
Arthur Scheinuk, owner of Scheinuk The Florist.
   He said he wanted tangible support for the display, not just
comments from people who walk into the store.
   ``Just to come here and say, `I was here as a young kid and now
I'm bringing my grandchildren,' without bringing some moral support
_ you ... get a little disgusted.''
   The fenced-in display, in which dozens of adult and baby rabbits
hop around a lawn or snuggle in wooden boxes cut to resemble
buildings along St. Charles Ave., opens 10 days before Easter and
lasts until Easter Sunday.
   Scheinuk said thousands of adults and children come to look at
the rabbits every year. Some buy them for $10.90 each _ a price at
which Scheinuk said he makes no profit.
   For the past several years, the display also has attracted
pickets, people who say selling live rabbits for Easter gifts
amounts to animal cruelty because the bunnies all too often wind up
at animal shelters.
   ``We suggested to them they would do beter telling unwed mothers
how to take care of their children,'' Scheinuk said.
   To add injury to insult, 15 rabbits were stolen late Thursday or
early Friday by someone who cut an 8-inch-square hole in the
chain-link cage.
   ``In this weather that we've had, these flooded conditions,
police have too much to do than to fool with rabbit stealers,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
