<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 1821EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MormonConference     04-02 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mormon Conference,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leader Says Church Growth Will Continue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Mormon Church on Saturday reported a
record increase in converts during 1987, and leaders warned members
against ostracizing non-Mormons in the church's Utah stronghold.
   Leaders also announced the appointment of two new members of the
leadership hierarchy and named a new president to the church's
organization for children.
   Mormon missionaries baptized 227,284 new members last year,
compared to 216,210 in 1986, according to the annual statistical
report of the 6.5-million-member church.
   The membership report was delivered on the opening day of the
158th Annual General Conference of The Church of Jesus Christ of
Latter-day Saints.
   The two-day conference has drawn thousands of Mormons from
around the world to hear sermons from the church's hierarchy,
including President Ezra Taft Benson, 88, who is considered a
prophet.
   Robert E. Sackley, 65, Bow Island, Canada, and L. Lionel
Kendrick, 56, Greenville, N.C., were named new members of the
Seventy, full-time clergy who assist the governing First Presidency
in directing the church. Sackley is currently president of the
church's mission in Nigeria, while Kendrick is directing missionary
efforts in the Tampa, Fla., area.
   Michaelene Packer Grassli was named president of the children's
program Primary. She succeeds Dwan J. Young, who is leaving the
position to accompany her husband, who has been appinted president
of the Calgary, Canada, Mission.
   The church's success in proselytizing has been accompanied by a
sharp increase in its missionary force, which has grown to 34,750
men and women, compared to 31,803 during 1986.
   ``Outside the church, many watch in amazement at this consistent
expansion, in spite of popular secularism,'' said David B. Haight
of the Council of the Twelve Apostles. The Twelve are full-time
clergy who assist the three-member First Presidency in directing
the church. The Seventy follow the Twelve in the hierarchy.
   But while leaders celebrated the growth, they warned members to
avoid religious arrogance, particularly in Utah, where non-members
often complain that they are excluded from politics and social life.
   About two-thirds of Utah's 1.6 million people are Mormon, and
church members hold nearly all major political offices. The
governor and the congressional delegation are members. More than 80
percent of the Legislature is Mormon, including the Senate
president, House speaker, and the majority leaders in both chambers.
   Numerical superiority does not justify disdain for those who are
not Mormon, said Dallin H. Oaks, a member of the Twelve and former
Utah Supreme Court justice.
   He said he recently received a letter in which the writer
complained that newcomers who are not Mormon arrive in Utah to find
themselves ``excluded at best and ostracized at worst.''
   That sentiment was demonstrated last week when Sacramento,
Calif., developer John Roberts turned down a job as chief of the
privately run Utah Economic Development Corp., saying the state has
an image of being inhospitable to non-Mormons. ``I was asked what
my religion was more in one afternoon in Salt Lake City than I have
in my entire life,'' Roberts said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
