<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HumorConference     04-02 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Humor Conference,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Even the Dullest Can Relate to Humor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.D. ``Dull'' Stewart,
self-proclaimed leader of International Dull Folks Unlimited,
crashed the seventh annual National Humor Conference Saturday to
panhandle for his mythical presidential candidacy.
   Stewart, a statistical analyst from Rochester, N.Y., became the
champion of dullards everywhere with the creation of DENSA, an
organization whose name stands for nothing except as a send-up of
the high-IQ society, Mensa.
   Talking to a roomful of professors gathered at Purdue University
for a serious study of humor in American society, Stewart made his
money pitch: ``I said I'm in room 228 in the Union Club. You can
just leave your $250 checks ouside the door. I haven't seen any
yet.''
   Stewart is actually a registered participant and welcome, said
Don Nilsen, an Arizona State University professor.
   Stewart's kind of self-deprecating humor won a nod of
appreciation from the professors. ``It's funny because it's a
reversal,'' said Nilsen. ``It's an opposite of expectations.
Whatever our frustrations are, we have ways of dealing with those
frustrations by using this kind of humor.''
   It's more sophisticated than one-liner humor that commonly
targets ethnic groups, politicians or sex, he said.
   ``It's a coping device,'' he said. ``You have to develop coping
devices for the real problems of the world.''
   Another researcher, Rhoda Lee Fisher of the State University of
New York, said Stewart's style has lot in common with many
successful professional comedians. Despite success and the
admiration of the audience, genuine self-doubt remains, she
explained.
   ``In fact, most comedians come across as being down and up at
the same time,'' she said. ``They tell us they're silly, but we
secretly know they are special and brave and doing something most
of us would not have the fortitude to attempt.''
   The four-day humor conference, attended by about 70 professors
from a variety of disciplines, runs through Monday. Studies will be
presented on humor and business management, the humor of
intentional mispronunciation, and a paper titled, ``The Continuing
Saga of Arizona's Governor: A Humorous Sequel.''
</TEXT>
