<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0600 04-02 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0600,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Campaigns in Colorado, Condemns Reagan Administration</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS grafs 11-12 pvs, `Jackson was ... average voters,' with
5 grafs to UPDATE with campaign appearances in Pueblo, Aspen,
spokeswoman comments on boom in contributions</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREELEY, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Jesse Jackson condemned the
Reagan administration Saturday for corruption and economic
suffering, telling striking meat workers, ``Reagan is on the way
out and we're on the way in.''
   Jackson began two days of campaigning among Colorado Democrats
who hold caucuses Monday night to apportion 45 delegates.
Wisconsin's important primary follows on Tuesday.
   Jackson didn't refer to his Democratic rivals, except for
ex-candidate Gary Hart, the former Colorado senator. ``Since my
friend Gary is out, I am Colorado's favorite son,'' he said.
   Jackson spoke to about 1,000 workers outside the Monfort Portion
Foods meatpacking plant, where workers have been on strike for
higher wages since Nov. 16.
   Jackson said there have been ``seven years of midnight'' under
President Reagan and Vice President George Bush. He referred to the
Easter season in encouraging strikers to continue to have hope.
   ``Innocent people do suffer _ that's one of the lessons of
Easter,'' the black preacher and civil rights activist told the
mostly white audience.
   ``But just because you're suffering, don't surrender,'' he said.
``In the end, faith will not disappoint. ...
   ``They could not stop the government from killing Jesus, but the
government could not stop new hope, could not stop resurrection,
could not stop renewal,'' he said. ``We cannot stop Reaganomics,
but Reaganomics cannot stop us. ... Reagan is on the way out and
we're on the way in _ we, the people, are on the way in.''
   Jackson, who with his Democratic rivals has called for the
resignation of Attorney General Edwin Meese III, blasted the Reagan
administration for what he said was corruption and contempt.
   ``The Iran-Contra scam expresses contempt for the law. We must
have a president who knows and respects the law, a president who
sets the moral tone for our nation,'' he said. ``We have in this
administration the most indictments, the most corruption, the
highest sleaze factor in the history of American government. We
deserve better government. We deserve honorable leaders.''
   Jackson received an enthusiastic response from about 2,000
people _ mainly white and Hispanic _ who gathered later at an
outdoor rally in Pueblo. He then headed to the mountain resort of
Aspen _ which had 1{ feet of snow last week _ where he was
attending a fund-raising event and speaking to a group of local
residents and skiers.
   Jackson's campaign said it had had its best success ever in
raising money during the past month.
   Campaign spokeswoman Denise Lee said the campaign raised $2.1
million during March, including $500,000 in the week since
Jackson's stunning victory in Michigan's caucuses. She said that
since Super Tuesday, the amount of money received by the campaign
by mail has increased from about $20,000 a day to $60,000 a day.
   Jackson planned to attend Easter services in Denver on Sunday
morning.
   In Greeley, Jackson repeated his common themes of attacking
corporations for exporting jobs and exploiting cheaper foreign
labor. He led the crowd in chanting that they would vote for
Jackson at caucuses around the state Monday night _ meetings called
``get togethers'' rather than by their formal name, which he said
was intimidating to average voters.
   He noted that they fall on April 4, the 20th anniversary of the
assassination of Martin Luther King Jr. in Memphis, Tenn., where
Jackson was present as a young aide to the civil rights leader.
   Answering questions after his speech, Jackson called efforts to
require only English to be taught as the main language in schools a
``mean-spirited mistake.''
</TEXT>
