<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru-Emergency     04-02 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Emergency,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Extends State of Emergency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Alan Garcia on Saturday extended a
state of emergency in an important mining region where leftist
guerrillas have repeatedly attacked mines and railroads.
   A decree in the official gazette, El Peruano, said the emergency
measures would be extended for another two months across the
mountainous eastern half of Pasco state. Cerro de Pasco, the state
capital, is 120 miles northeast of Lima.
   Pasco is the center of Peru's vital mining industry that
provides more than 50 percent of the nation's foreign exchange.
Maoist Shining Path guerrillas have made hundreds of attacks in the
zone in an effort to cripple Peru's economy.
   The government began decreeing states of emergency in November
1980 because of the insurgency. Parts of seven states, including
Lima, currently are under states of emergency.
   A state of emergency suspends citizens' rights to travel and
assemble freely and permits government forces to conduct searches
without warrants and hold suspects for lengthy periods without
filing charges.
   The government says more than 10,000 people have been killed in
violence related to the Shining Path's eight-year-old campaign to
gain power.
</TEXT>
