<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 2003EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Zimbabwe     04-02 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zimbabwe,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Party Votes To Merge With Government Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANGUS SHAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The party of former opposition leader
Joshua Nkomo voted Saturday to merge with the ruling party of Prime
Minister Robert Mugabe in a step to unite the nation's most
powerful political movements.
   Nkomo, president of the Zimbabwe African People's Union, opened
the party's one-day congress with a plea to more than 5,000
delegates to endorse a unity accord he signed with Mugabe on Dec.
23.
   Nkomo said, ``This accord opens up broad vistas for the economy
of the country through the participation of all the people in
development.''
   Nkomo, 70, needed a simple majority vote to endorse the merger
but the congress passed two resolutions by unanimous vote. The
resolutions approved the merger and asked Nkomo and Mugabe to
proceed with uniting their parties' structures under one banner,
effectively dismantling Nkomo's party.
   ``This country will owe a lot to your decisions,'' Nkomo said
after the vote. ``We have a collective vision. We must stand
together. We must not deceive each other.''
   Mugabe's Zimbabwe African National Union is to vote on the unity
accord on April 9.
   Mugabe and Nkomo originally were allies in the campaign to bring
majority black rule to the country that was the white-ruled British
colony of Rhodesia.
   In 1963, Mugabe and some other officials left Nkomo's party to
form their own leftist movement.
   Both parties were outlawed by then-Prime Minister Ian Smith's
white-dominated government in 1964. Nkomo and Mugabe, along with
hundreds of other black nationalists, were detained for more than a
decade.
   Mugabe and Nkomo then became leaders in a seven-year guerrilla
war that ended when the country became independent on April 18,
1980. The alliance Mugabe and Nkomo had formed during the war came
apart after Mugabe's party won Zimbabwe's first election after
independence.
   Nkomo and Mugabe remained political foes until Dec. 23, when
they signed the unity accord that signaled an end to frequent
fighting between their supporters. In January Nkomo was appointed
one of three senior Cabinet ministers in a government shuffle.
   If both parties approve the merger, Mugabe, 64, will have the
support of all but one legislator in the 100-seat National Assembly
and the 40-member Senate. He needs the vote of all 140 lawmakers to
change the constitution and establish a one-party socialist state
that he advocates.
   The dissident lawmaker is businessman Goodson Sithole, but
political observers say he could join Mugabe's party before a vote
is taken in Parliament later this year.
   In another development, a gang of men stabbed to death a white
Zimbabwean farmer at his home and beat his wife unconscious, police
reported Saturday.
   They said the body of Johannes Du Toit, 55, was found by the
family cook Friday in the farmhouse near the town of Karoi, 112
miles northwest of Harare.
   Police said they had not determined the motive, but neighbors
who spoke on condition of anonymity said Du Toit recently had
argued with some of his black employees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
