<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Robertson     04-02 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robertson,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Sees Role as Conservative `Rallying Point'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HILLIARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson said Saturday he would stay in the
race for the Republican nomination for president primarily because,
``I want to be a rallying point for conservatives.''
   ``I am the only conservative in the race, because George Bush is
considered to be a moderate,'' Robertson told reporters as he
campaigned in Colorado before Monday's precinct caucuses.
   ``There couldn't be anything more deadly than to be taken off
the evening news and off the front page of the newspaper, and that
is what is going to happen as soon as George Bush has it locked
up,'' Robertson said.
   At a news conference before a rally at the Sheraton Denver Tech
Center on Saturday afternoon, Robertson was asked about his role at
the Republican National Convention in New Orleans in August.
   ``I want to address the issues _ how we stand on taxes and
following the Reagan agenda,'' the former television evangelist
said, adding he believes the 1984 Republican platform should be
retained.
   ``I like the '84 GOP platform very much,'' he said, defining it
as a conservative position on strong defense, conservative judges,
fighting communism, lowering taxes ``and being less intrusive in
the lives of people.''
   The rally audience _ estimated by police at 400 people _
received information sheets placed on each seat that instructed
them in ways to be important factors Monday night at Colorado's
precinct caucuses, the starting point for sending 36 delegates to
the New Orleans convention.
   ``Keep your preference under wraps _ unknown!'' the sheet told
the audience members, adding that they should ``be polite'' but
should try to find out who people are supporting for president
``carefully.''
   Robertson's speech at the rally emphasized the importance of the
family, the need for winning the war against drugs and AIDS and
bringing God back into public school classrooms.
   He told the audience: ``I am going to be the champion of the
Christian and conservative points of view ... if it takes until
1992 to do it.''
   Robertson planned to give an Easter Sunday sermon to an
estimated 5,000 people in four congregations in the Denver area.
   Campaign aides said they had up to 10 phone bank operators
trying to persuade at least 10,000 people to show up for caucuses
Monday night. ``Our goal would be to have 15,000,'' said David
Nelson, a Denver businessman who is coordinating Robertson's
Colorado campaign.
</TEXT>
