<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Obit-Thomson 2ndLd-Writethru a0640 04-02 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Thomson, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0640,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Wisconsin Governor, Congressman Vernon Thomson Dies</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Adds two grafs at bottom to UPDATE with funeral arrangements
and survivors.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vernon W. Thomson, a former Wisconsin
governor, member of Congress for 14 years and Federal Election
Commission chairman, died Saturday at George Washington University
Hospital, a spokeswoman said. He was 82.
   Yvonne Hiott, the hospital spokeswoman, said the cause of death
was respiratory arrest. She said Thomson, who lived in the
Washington suburb of McLean, Va., had been in the hospital since
March 25.
   Thomson, a Republican member of the Wisconsin state assembly
between 1935-51 and speaker for three consecutive terms, served as
Wisconsin's governor in 1956 and 1957. He was elected to the U.S.
House of Representatives in November 1960, and served through 1974.
   After leaving Congress, he joined the FEC and remained there
until 1979, serving in 1976-77 as its chairman.
   In 1981, then-President Jimmy Carter called Thomson out of
retirement to serve a year as interim member of the commission.
   Carter's request that he rejoin the FEC illustrated the
government's respect for Thomson, said former Rep. Glenn R. Davis,
R-Wis., who described Thomson as a friend ever since they served in
the Wisconsin legislature together in the 1940s.
   ``He served longer than he was supposed to,'' Davis said
Saturday. ``I think he was one of the most respected members who
ever served in the House.''
   Born in Richland Center, Wis., Thomson attended Carroll College
and the University of Wisconsin Law School before serving as
Richland County district attorney in the 1930s and as Richland
Center mayor.
   After serving in the state legislature, he was elected state
attorney general in 1950, 1952 and 1954 before being named governor
for two years. He lost a re-election bid to the statehouse.
   Davis said Thomson's re-election defeat in 1958 was the only
serious setback in his political career.
   ``Unfortunately, 1958 was a bad year for Republicans,'' Davis
said.
   Thomson is survived by three children _ Vernon Jr. of McLean,
Patricia Thomson of Fletcher, Va., and Susan Thomson Turner of
Vienna, Va. _ and two grandchildren. His wife, the former Helen A.
Davis, died in 1973.
   Funeral services were scheduled for Thursday at Pratt funeral
home in Richland Center. Burial will be at the Richland Center
Cemetery.
</TEXT>
