<HEAD>Robeson County Indians Write Letter To Soviet Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAYETTEVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Robeson County Indians charged in
the armed takeover of a Lumberton newspaper said they have written
to Soviet General Secretary Mikhail Gorbachev.
   The letters will be delivered to Moscow by attorney William
Kunstler, who hopes to make Indian rights an issue at the May
summit between Gorbachev and President Reagan, said Eddie Hatcher
on Saturday.
   Hatcher, 30, and Timothy Jacobs, 19, both of Pembroke, are
charged with hostage-taking and the manufacture and possession of
illegal weapons in connection with the Feb. 1 siege of The
Robesonian newspaper in Lumberton.
   ``We raised several issues in our letters regarding the Reagan
administration and past administrations' treatment of native
Americans that has been brought about by lies and broken
treaties,'' Hatcher said in a telephone interview with the
Fayetteville Observer-Times. ``We are political prisoners, and we
raise the fact that there are many other political prisoners like
us.''
   Hatcher and Jacobs, both Tuscarora Indians, have said that
mistreatment of minorities in Robeson County led them to take over
the newspaper offices.
   They released their hostages eight hours after the siege began
following a commitment by Gov. Jim Martin to appoint a task force
to study the Indians' claims agains the Robeson County government
and law enforcement agencies.
</TEXT>
