<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0514 04-02 0796</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0514,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Lowers Rhetoric, Expectations in Central America</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 11th graf pvs bgng, `The official,' with 3 grafs and
penultimate graf pvs bgng, `Talks on,' with 1 graf to UPDATE with
Contras delaying scheduled Wednesday start of negotiations</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA </BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The guns are silent for the time being in
Nicaragua and there is even a truce of sorts between Republicans
and Democrats on the contentious issue of aid to the Nicaraguan
Contra rebels.
   And as Nicaragua's leftist government and the U.S.-backed rebels
prepare to negotiate a settlement to end their six-year war, the
Reagan administration has remained uncharacteristically silent, no
longer using apocalyptic terms to discuss its perception of the
stakes involved.
   Along with its rhetoric, the administration is lowering its
expectations of its ability to influence events in the region. But
most officials believe the Sandinista government is going into the
peace talks in a commanding position because of Contra military
weakness.
   For now, almost everyone, from the Sandinista government to
administration and congressional hardliners, believes the peace
process should be allowed to go forward without guns ablaze.
   Just a few weeks ago, bipartisanship on the Contra aid issue
seemed beyond reach. An administration aid proposal was defeated
narrowly in the House on Feb. 3 and a substitute Democratic plan
also was rejected by a slim margin a few weeks later.
   But this past week, both houses of Congress overwhelmingly
approved a $48 million package providing humanitarian aid for the
Contras as well as for children on both sides who have been injured
in the conflict. The package includes $10 million for independent
verification of the cease-fire agreement.
   Following Contra acquiescence to a 60-day cease-fire on March
23, both Republicans and Democrats agreed that this type of aid
package was the only option available to them. But the legislation
also includes a promise by House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, that
he will not block ``fair and orderly'' consideration of a new
military aid request if the peace talks collapse due to Sandinista
intransigence.
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., noted that the aid bill did not
provide weapons for the rebels, as Contra supporters had hoped. And
it went too far for Contra opponents, who object to sending any aid.
   ``This package strikes a balance,'' Dodd said during an
unusually harmonious floor debate on the proposal last Thursday.
   Dodd said the sole purpose of the package is to support the
cease-fire agreement: ``If not for that agreement, we wouldn't be
doing this today.''
   The official administration line is that the temporary
cease-fire was a step forward, and it is now up to the disputants
to resolve their differences at the bargaining table when peace
talks begin.
   Those talks were scheduled to begin Wednesday, but the Contras
said Saturday they would delay the talks for one week to provide
more time for technical commissions of both sides to work out
details of the five zones inside Nicaragua where rebel forces are
to gather under the provisions of the cease-fire accord.
   But a government statement signed Saturday by Deputy Foreign
Minister Victor Hugo Tinoco stressed it was ``extremely important''
to comply with the cease-fire pact's timetable and stick by the
April 6 meeting date.
   The administration's low-key attitude was symbolized by
President Reagan's decision on Friday to sign the aid legislation
in his White House residence, forgoing the ceremonial fanfare that
attends some bill-signings.
   The administration has long contended that the Sandinistas will
be forced to democratize and demilitarize only through Contra
military pressure, or at least the threat of it.
   Just last February, Reagan said the Sandinista government ``will
be free to continue the consolidation of their totalitarian regime,
the military buildup inside Nicaragua and communist subversion of
their neighbors'' if military aid to the Contras stops.
   The administration has not renounced Reagan's grim prediction
but it appears that an informal moratorium has been placed on that
type of rhetoric.
   Things have been quiet in Nicaragua as well. A formal cease-fire
replaced the temporary one on Friday, and the Nicaraguan Defense
Ministry reported no violations.
   Many Nicaraguans marked the long Easter weekend by taking
vacations at beaches on the Pacific coast. Banks, government
offices, stores and most restaurants were closed until Monday.
   When talks on a permanent truce begin, the Contras are expected
to issue demands for 17 democratic reforms, abolition of the draft,
the repatriation Soviet bloc military advisers and other measures.
   In effect, they will be asking the Sandinistas to negotiate the
revolution, something the government has said it would never do.
The process is not expected to be free of friction.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   George Gedda has covered foreign affairs for The
Associated Press since 1968.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
