<DOCNO> AP880402-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-88 0616EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DigestBriefs 1stLd-Writethru a9010 04-02 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Digest Briefs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a9010,0620</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Deletes non-budgeted LOS ANGELES-dated item on Shultz,
UNDATED Political Rdp item, and MANILA-dated item on Honasan
escape; SUBS Washington-dated item on Meese to correct time element
to Friday, sted today.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Independent Counsel James C. McKay said there
was insufficient evidence ``developed to date'' to warrant a
criminal indictment of Attorney General Edwin Meese III in
connection with the Iraq-Jordan pipeline plan or his investment in
telephone company stock.
   Meese said he was ``gratified by the action and the statement''
issued Friday and indicated he would not resign his post.
   ``I would urge that there be no rush to judgment,'' Meese told a
news conference.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration, expressing concern
about the safety of Americans in Panama, has decided to dispatch
another 1,300 military personnel to the troubled Central American
nation.
   Among the units being ordered south is an Army aviation task
force that includes helicopter gunships.
   The Pentagon announced the decision to increase the number of
troops in Panama late Friday evening ``in view of the growing
unrest and tension'' in that country. The deployments are to begin
Tuesday and be completed by April 8.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers were off the streets as
Easter weekend began and a jailed opposition leader's wife said her
husband was being held hostage in Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega's
effort to maintain power.
   Also Friday, the Pentagon said it was sending 1,300 more
military personnel to protect U.S. bases and thousands of American
residents, bringing to nearly 12,000 the number of U.S. troops in
Panama.
   Opposition leaders said they planned to meet today or Sunday to
decide whether to lift a 12-day-old general strike that has shut
down most commercial activity in an effort to oust Noriega,
Panama's de facto leader and heads of its 15,000-member Defense
Forces.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With fewer Holy Week visitors than usual
because of the Arab uprising in its occupied lands, Israel sought
to ensure the safety of the thousands of Christians who had come
for Easter Sunday observances.
   Friday was stained by bloodshed as Christians commemorated Good
Friday, Jews began the start of the week-long Passover festival and
angry Moslems rioted as they left mosques after morning prayers.
   Police and troops were reinforced in and around Jerusalem's holy
sites to protect participants at Easter ceremonies by Christians
celebrating their belief that Christ was resurrected two days after
dying on a cross.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp., the winner in a bitter two-month
battle for Federated Department Stores Inc., says it will keep the
``crown jewels'' of the nation's fifth-largest retailer and sell
off the rest of the company.
   The Toronto-based developer agreed Friday to acquire Federated
for $73.50 a share, or $6.58 billion, beating out rival suitor R.H.
Macy & Co., which had reached a merger agreement last month.
   The acquisition would be the fifth-largest corporate takeover in
U.S. history, and the largest deal not involving oil companies.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Overseas Brats, a magazine for
Americans who went to high school half a world away from their
homeland, is helping them find classmates they haven't seen for
years, says its Army brat publisher.
   ``The difference between stateside graduates and Army brats, Air
Force brats, Navy juniors and others is that those in stateside
have a hometown to go to for a reunion,'' said publisher and editor
Joe Condrill.
   ``But the brats, after they graduate, they leave the military
environment and sometimes are lost,'' he said.
</TEXT>
